{"title_page": "The Last Debate", "text_new": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name        = The Last Debate\n| image       = The Last Debate.jpg\n| caption     =\n| writer      = [[Jim Lehrer]]<br/>Jon Maas\n| starring    = [[James Garner]]<br>[[Peter Gallagher]]<br>[[Audra McDonald]]<br>[[Marco Sanchez]]\n| director    = [[John Badham]]\n| producer    =\n| company = [[Scott Free Productions]]\n| distributor = [[Showtime (TV channel)|Showtime]]\n| released    = {{Film date|2000}}\n| runtime     = 96 minutes\n| country     = United States\n| language    = English\n| budget      =\n}}\n'''''The Last Debate''''' is a 2000 political [[television film]] directed by [[John Badham]], based on the book by [[journalist]] and [[writer]] [[Jim Lehrer]], with a [[teleplay]] by Jon Mass,<ref>{{cite web|title=The Last Debate|url=https://www.amazon.com/Last-Debate-Jim-Lehrer/dp/1586480049/|work=Books|publisher=Amazon.com|accessdate=4 October 2012}}</ref> and starring [[James Garner]] and [[Peter Gallagher]].\n\n==Synopsis==\nA televised presidential debate has a conspiracy behind it.\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* [[James Garner]] as Mike Howley\n* [[Peter Gallagher]] as Tom Chapman\n* [[Audra McDonald]] as Barbara Manning\n* [[Donna Murphy]] as Joan Naylor\n* [[Marco Sanchez]] as Henry Ramirez\n* [[Dorian Harewood]] as Brad Lily\n* [[Jack Turpin]] as Michael Riley\n* [[Bruce Gray]] as Governor Paul L. Greene\n* [[Stephen Young (actor)|Stephen Young]] as Richard Meredith\n* [[Lawrence Dane]] as Sidney Robert Mulvane\n* [[Djanet Sears]] as Nancy Dewey\n* [[Peter Donaldson]] as Jeff Grayson\n* [[John Badham]] as Don Beard\n* [[Leslie Carlson]] as Pat Tubbs\n* [[Maggie Huculak]] as Gwyn Garrison\n* [[Martin Doyle]] as Jim Weaver\n* [[Brenda Robins]] as Carol Reynolds\n* [[Colin Fox (actor)|Colin Fox]] as Joshua L. Simpson\n* [[Judah Katz]] as Bob Lucas\n* [[Robin Ward (television personality)|Robin Ward]] as Mark Southeran\n* [[Don Ritchie]] as Church Hammond\n* [[Nicky Guadagni]] as Sam Minter\n* [[Patrice Goodman]] as Roz Weisberg\n* [[Barry Flatman]] as Ned Cannon\n* [[Shelley Peterson]] as Joyce Meredith\n* [[Annabelle Torsein]] as Alison Meredith\n* [[Lynn Vogt]] as Ellen Greene\n* [[Eamon Zekkon]] as TV Director\n* [[Barbara Gordon (actress)|Barbara Gordon]] as Lorraine Hampstead\n* [[Nancy Harewood]] as Bonnie Kerr\n* [[Ann Marin]] as Female Reporter\n* [[Vanessa Vaughan]] as Grace Dickins\n* [[Doug Murray (actor)|Doug Murray]] as Jeff Field\n* Martin Roach as Room Service Waiter\n* [[Denis Akiyama]] as TV Makeup Artist\n* [[Bryan Renfro]] as Steve Harrington\n* [[Sharron Matthews]] as Barbara Fan\n* [[Chuck Campbell]] as Bartender\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|id=0249683|title=The Last Debate}}\n\n{{John Badham}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Last Debate, The}}\n[[Category:2000 films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:American television films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by John Badham]]\n[[Category:Scott Free Productions films]]\n[[Category:Showtime (TV network) films]]\n\n\n{{US-tv-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name        = The Last Debate\n| image       = The Last Debate.jpg\n| caption     =\n| writer      = [[Jim Lehrer]]<br/>Jon Maas\n| starring    = [[James Garner]]<br>[[Peter Gallagher]]<br>[[Audra McDonald]]<br>[[Marco Sanchez]]\n| director    = [[John Badham]]\n| producer    =\n| company = [[Scott Free Productions]]\n| distributor = [[Showtime (TV channel)|Showtime]]\n| released    = {{Film date|2000}}\n| runtime     = 96 minutes\n| country     = United States\n| language    = English\n| budget      =\n}}\n'''''The Last Debate''''' is a 2000 political [[television film]] directed by [[John Badham]], based on the book by [[journalist]] and [[writer]] [[Jim Lehrer]], with a [[teleplay]] by Jon Mass,<ref>{{cite web|title=The Last Debate|url=https://www.amazon.com/Last-Debate-Jim-Lehrer/dp/1586480049/|work=