 peoples|Turkic tribes]]\n\n=== [[Americas]] ===\n{{See also|Americas (terminology)}}\n\n* ''by the United Nations Statistics Division's geoscheme (see also: [[United Nations geoscheme for the Americas|UN geoscheme for the Americas]]):''\n** [[Latin America]] and the [[Caribbean]]     \n*** [[Caribbean]]<ref name=subreg>These three subregions together form the [[continent]] of [[North America]].</ref> \u2013 the UN includes the [[Lucayan Archipelago]] in this subregion\n*** [[Latin America]]\n**** [[Central America]]<ref name=subreg /> \u2013 the UN includes [[Clipperton Island]] and [[Mexico]] in this subregion\n**** [[South America]]\n** [[Northern America]]<ref name=subreg />\n\n* ''by culture:''\n** [[Anglo-America]]\n** [[French America]]\n** [[Latin America]]\n*** [[Ibero-America]]\n**** [[Hispanic America]]\n***** [[Mesoamerica]]\n**** [[Portuguese colonization of the Americas|Portuguese America]]\n\n==== [[North America]] ====\n* ''by geography:''\n** [[Middle America (Americas)|Middle America]]\n*** [[Central America]]\n*** [[Clipperton Island]]\n*** [[Mexico]]\n*** [[West Indies]]\n**** [[Caribbean]]\n***** [[Antilles]]\n****** [[Greater Antilles]]\n******* [[Hispaniola]]\n****** [[Lesser Antilles]]\n******* [[Leeward Islands]]\n******** [[SSS Islands]]\n******* [[Southern Caribbean]]\n******** [[Leeward Antilles]]\n********* [[ABC Islands (Leeward Antilles)|ABC Islands]]\n******** [[Windward Islands]]\n***** [[Bajo Nuevo Bank]]\n***** [[Archipelago of San Andr\u00e9s, Providencia and Santa Catalina|San Andr\u00e9s and Providencia]]\n***** [[Serranilla Bank]]\n**** [[Lucayan Archipelago]]\n** [[Northern America]]\n*** [[Bermuda]]\n*** [[Canada]]\n**** [[Eastern Canada]]\n***** [[Atlantic Canada]]\n****** [[The Maritimes]]\n***** [[Central Canada]]\n**** [[Northern Canada]]\n***** [[Arctic Archipelago|Canadian Arctic Archipelago]]\n**** [[Western Canada]]\n***** [[Canadian Prairies]]\n***** [[British Columbia|West Coast]]\n*** [[Greenland]]\n*** [[Saint Pierre and Miquelon]]\n*** [[United States]] (excluding [[Hawaii]])\n**** [[Alaska]]\n**** [[Contiguous United States]]\n***** [[Central United States]]\n****** [[Midwestern United States]]\n***** [[Eastern United States]]\n****** [[Northeastern United States]]\n****** [[Southeastern United States]]\n***** [[Northern United States]]\n****** [[Great Lakes region]] (including [[Ontario]], [[Canada]])\n***** [[Southern United States]]\n****** [[South Central United States]]\n***** [[Western United States]] (including [[Alaska]] and [[Hawaii]])\n****** [[Northwestern United States]]\n****** [[Southwestern United States]] (some geographers include the [[Oklahoma Panhandle]] and [[West Texas]] in this subregion)\n\n* ''by physiography:''\n** [[Atlantic coastal plain]]\n** [[Atlantic Seaboard Fall Line]]\n** [[East Coast of the United States]]\n** [[Great Basin]]\n** [[Great Basin Desert]]\n** [[Great Lakes]]\n** [[Great Lakes Basin]]\n** [[Great Plains]]\n** [[Piedmont (United States)|Piedmont]]\n** [[West Coast of the United States]]\n\n* ''by geopolitics:''\n** [[Dutch Caribbean]]\n*** [[Caribbean Netherlands]] (aka the [[Caribbean Netherlands|BES Islands]])\n** [[Organisation of Eastern Caribbean States]]\n** [[Virgin Islands]]\n*** [[British Virgin Islands]]\n*** [[Spanish Virgin Islands]]\n*** [[United States Virgin Islands]]\n** [[Western Caribbean Zone]]\n\n* ''by economics:''\n** [[Caribbean Community|Caribbean Community (CARICOM)]]\n** [[Central America Free Trade Agreement|Central America Free Trade Agreement (CAFTA)]]\n** [[Great Lakes Megalopolis]]\n** [[Mesoamerican region]]\n** [[North American Free Trade Agreement|North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA)]]\n** [[Northeast megalopolis]]\n** [[Organisation of Eastern Caribbean States]]\n** [[Petrocaribe]]\n\n* ''by geology:''\n** [[Canadian Shield]]\n** [[North American craton]]\n** [[Slave craton]]\n** [[Superior craton]]\n** [[Wyoming craton]]\n\n==== [[South America]] ====\n* ''by geography:''\n** [[Altiplano]]\n** [[Amazon Basin]]\n** [[Andean states]]\n** [[Andes]]\n** [[Brazilian Highlands]]\n** [[Caribbean South America]]\n** [[Gran Chaco]]\n** [[The Guianas|Guianan states]]\n** [[Pampa]]\n** [[Pantanal]]\n** [[Patagonia]]\n** [[Southern Cone]]\n\n* ''by economics:''\n** [[Andean Community]]\n** [[Mercosur]]\n** [[Union of South American Nations]]\n\n* ''by geology:'' \n** [[Guiana Shield]]\n\n=== [[Antarctica]] ===\n* ''by the United Nations Statistics Division's geoscheme:''\n** [[Antarctica]]\n\n* ''by geography:''\n** [[List of Antarctic and subantarctic islands|Antarctic and subantarctic islands]]\n*** [[Bouvet Island]] (some geographers consider it as part of [[Africa]])\n*** [[French Southern and Antarctic Lands]] (some geographers consider them as part of [[Africa]])\n*** [[Heard Island and McDonald Islands]] (some geographers consider them as part of [[Africa]])\n*** [[Macquarie Island]] (some geographers consider it as part of [[Oceania]])\n*** [[New Zealand Subantarctic Islands]] (some geographers consider them as part of [[Oceania]])\n*** [[Peter I Island]]\n*** [[Prince Edward Islands]] (some geographers consider them as part of [[Africa]])\n*** [[South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands]] (some geographers consider them as part of [[South America]])\n*** [[South Orkney Islands]]\n*** [[South Shetland Islands]]\n** [[Antarctica|Mainland Antarctica]]\n*** [[Antarctic Peninsula]]\n*** [[East Antarctica]]\n*** [[Transantarctic Mountains]]\n*** [[West Antarctica]]\n\n=== [[Oceania]] ===\n* ''by the United Nations Statistics Division's geoscheme (see also: [[United Nations geoscheme for Oceania|UN geoscheme for Oceania]]):''\n** [[Australia]] and [[New Zealand]] \u2013 the UN includes the [[Elizabeth Reef|Elizabeth]] and [[Middleton Reef|Middleton Reefs]], [[Lord Howe Island|Lord Howe Island Group]] and [[Norfolk Island]] in this subregion\n** [[Melanesia]] \u2013 the UN includes [[New Caledonia]] and [[New Guinea]] in this subregion\n** [[Micronesia]]\n** [[Polynesia]] \u2013 the UN excludes [[New Zealand]] from this subregion\n\n* ''by geography:''\n** [[Australasia]]\n*** [[Australia (continent)]]\n**** [[Australia]]\n***** [[Ashmore and Cartier Islands]] (some geographers consider them as part of [[Southeast Asia]])\n***** [[Australian Capital Territory]]\n***** [[Christmas Island]] (some geographers consider it as part of [[Southeast Asia]])\n***** [[Cocos (Keeling) Islands]] (some geographers consider them as part of [[Southeast Asia]])\n***** [[Coral Sea Islands|Coral Sea Islands Territory]] (excluding the [[Elizabeth Reef|Elizabeth]] and [[Middleton Reef|Middleton Reefs]])\n***** [[Jervis Bay Territory]]\n***** [[New South Wales]] (excluding the [[Lord Howe Island|Lord Howe Island Group]])\n***** [[Northern Territory]]\n***** [[Queensland]]\n***** [[South Australia]]\n***** [[Tasmania]]\n***** [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]]\n***** [[Western Australia]]\n**** [[New Guinea]] (some geographers consider it as part of [[Melanesia]])\n***** [[Papua New Guinea]]\n***** [[Western New Guinea]]\n****** [[Papua (province)|Papua]]\n****** [[West Papua (province)|West Papua]]\n*** [[Zealandia]]\n**** [[Elizabeth Reef|Elizabeth]] and [[Middleton Reef|Middleton Reefs]]\n**** [[Lord Howe Island|Lord Howe Island Group]]\n**** [[New Caledonia]] (also part of [[Melanesia]])\n**** [[New Zealand]] (excluding the [[Kermadec Islands]], some geographers consider it as part of [[Polynesia]])\n**** [[Norfolk Island]]\n** [[List of islands in the Pacific Ocean|Pacific Islands]]\n*** [[Melanesia]] (some geographers consider it as part of [[Australasia]])\n*** [[Micronesia]] (including the [[Bonin Islands]] and [[Volcano Islands]])\n*** [[Polynesia]] (including [[Easter Island]], [[Hawaii]], the [[Kermadec Islands]] and [[Isla Salas y G\u00f3mez|Salas y G\u00f3mez Island]])\n\n* ''by geology (see also: [[Geology of Australia]]):''\n** [[Archean|Archaean]]\n** [[Australian Shield]]\n** [[Centralian Superbasin]]\n** [[Gawler Craton]]\n** [[Narryer gneiss]]\n** [[Ore genesis]]\n** [[Perth Basin]]\n** [[Pilbara Craton]]\n** [[Western Plateau]]\n** [[Yilgarn Craton]]\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Autonomous area#Autonomous region|Autonomous region]]\n* [[Committee of the Regions]]\n* [[Continent]]\n* [[Continental fragment]]\n* [[Euroregion]]\n* [[Latin names of regions]]\n* [[Military district]]\n* [[Polar region]]\n* [[Region]]\n* [[Regional district]]\n* [[Regional municipality]]\n* [[Subcontinent]]\n* [[Submerged continents]]\n* [[Supercontinent]]\n* [[United Nations geoscheme]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://unstats.un.org/unsd/geoinfo/ungegn.htm UN Group of Experts on Geographical Names]\n* [http://unstats.un.org/unsd/methods/m49/m49regin.htm UN Statistics Division's Country and Area Codes Classifications]\n\n{{Continents of the world}}\n{{Regions of the world}}\n\n[[Category:Administrative territorial entities by type]]\n", "text_old": "A '''subregion''' is a part of a larger [[region]] or [[continent]] and is usually based on location. [[Cardinal direction]]s, such as [[south]] or southern, are commonly used to define a subregion.\n\n== United Nations subregions ==\n{{Main|United Nations geoscheme}}\n\n[[File:United Nations geographical subregions.png|thumb|350px|right|The [[United Nations geoscheme|UN geoscheme]], created by the [[United Nations Statistics Division|UN Statistics Division]]. For statistical consistency and for convenience, each [[country]] or area is shown in one region only: e.g., [[Russia]] ([[Eastern Europe]]), which is in [[Europe]] and [[Asia]].]]\n\nThe [[United Nations Statistics Division|Statistics Division]] of the [[United Nations]] (UN) is in charge of the collection, processing, and dissemination of statistical information for the UN.<ref>[http://millenniumindicators.un.org/unsd/aboutus.htm United Nations Statistics Division - About Us]</ref> In 1999, it developed a system of macro-geographical (continental) regions, subregions, and other selected economic groups to report advances towards achieving numerous [[Millennium Development Goals|millennial development goals]] worldwide. These [[United Nations geoscheme|statistical divisions]] were devised for statistical purposes and is used for carrying out statistical analysis.<ref>[http://millenniumindicators.un.org/unsd/methods/m49/m49regin.htm United Nations Statistics Division - Standard Country and Area Codes Classifications]</ref> The division's first publication was the book ''World's Women 2000: Trends and Statistics'' in 2000.\n \nAccording to the UN, the assignment of countries or areas to specific groupings is for statistical convenience and does not imply any assumption regarding political or other affiliation of countries or territories.<ref>[http://unstats.un.org/unsd/methods/m49/m49.htm Standard country or area codes and geographical regions for statistical use]</ref>\n\n== Subregions by continent ==\nThe following is a non-exhaustive list of subregions, arranged alphabetically by region (i.e., by continent); in the UN geoscheme, higher-level, macro-geographical regions are arranged to the extent possible according to continents.  \n\n=== [[Afro-Eurasia]] ===\n==== [[Africa]] ====\n* ''by the United Nations Statistics Division's geoscheme (see also: [[United Nations geoscheme for Africa|UN geoscheme for Africa]]):''\n** [[North Africa|Northern Africa]]\n** [[Sub-Saharan Africa]]\n*** [[East Africa|Eastern Africa]]\n*** [[Central Africa|Middle Africa]]\n*** [[Southern Africa]]\n*** [[West Africa|Western Africa]]\n\n* ''by geography:''\n** [[North Africa]] (aka [[Sahara|Saharan Africa]])\n*** [[Maghreb]] (aka [[Maghreb|Northwest Africa]], also including [[Mauritania]], which most geographers consider it as part of [[West Africa]], some geographers consider [[Libya]] as part of Northeast Africa and [[Western Sahara]] as part of [[West Africa]])\n** [[Sub-Saharan Africa]]\n*** [[Central Africa]] (aka [[Congo Basin|Congo]], [[Central Africa|Middle Africa]], [[Equatorial Africa]] or [[Tropical Africa]])\n*** [[East Africa]]\n**** [[Horn of Africa]] (aka [[Horn of Africa|Northeast Africa]], some geographers consider [[Egypt]], [[Libya]] and [[Sudan]] as Northeast Africa instead)\n**** [[Southeast Africa]] (also including [[Botswana]], [[Eswatini]] and [[Lesotho]], which most geographers consider them as part of [[Southern Africa]])\n*** [[Southern Africa]]\n*** [[West Africa]] (aka [[Guinea (region)|Guinea]])\n\n* ''by physiography:''\n** [[Congo Basin]]\n** [[Guinea (region)]]\n** [[Sahara]]\n** [[Sahel]]\n** [[Sudan (region)]]\n*** [[Sudanian Savanna]]\n**** [[East Sudanian Savanna]]\n***** [[Sudd]]\n**** [[Sudanian Savanna|West Sudanian Savanna]]\n\n* ''by geology:''\n** [[Kaapvaal Craton]]\n** [[Zimbabwe Craton]]\n\n==== [[Eurasia]] ====\n===== [[Asia]] =====\n* ''by the United Nations Statistics Division's geoscheme (see also: [[United Nations geoscheme for Asia|UN geoscheme for Asia]]):''\n** [[Central Asia]]\n** [[East Asia|Eastern Asia]]\n** [[Southeast Asia|Southeastern Asia]]\n** [[South Asia|Southern Asia]]\n** [[Western Asia]]\n\n* ''by geography:''\n** [[Central Asia]]\n** [[East Asia]]\n*** [[Greater China]]\n**** [[China]]\n***** [[Hong Kong]] (some geographers consider it as part of [[Northeast Asia]])\n***** [[Macau]] (some geographers consider it as part of [[Northeast Asia]])\n***** [[Mainland China]] (some geographers consider it as part of [[Northeast Asia]])\n****** [[North China]] (Eastern [[Inner Mongolia]] is also part of [[Northeast China]])\n****** [[Northeast China]] (also part of [[Northeast Asia]])\n****** [[List of regions of China|Southeast China]]\n******* [[East China]] (some geographers include [[Taiwan|Taiwan Island]], [[Penghu]], [[Kinmen]], [[Matsu Islands|Matsu]] and the [[Senkaku Islands]] in this subregion)\n******* [[South Central China]]\n******** [[Central China]]\n******** [[South China]] (including [[Hainan|Hainan Island]] and the [[South China Sea Islands]], some geographers also include [[Hong Kong]] and [[Macau]] in this subregion)\n****** [[Western China]]\n******* [[Northwest China]] (some geographers consider [[Qinghai]] and [[Xinjiang]] as part of [[Central Asia]])\n******* [[Southwest China]] (some geographers consider [[Tibet Autonomous Region|Tibet]] as part of [[Central Asia]])\n**** [[South China Sea Islands]] (some geographers consider them as part of [[Northeast Asia]])\n***** [[Paracel Islands]]\n***** [[Pratas Islands]]\n***** [[Scarborough Shoal]]\n***** [[Spratly Islands]]\n****** [[James Shoal]]\n***** [[Zhongsha Islands]]\n****** [[Macclesfield Bank]]\n**** [[Taiwan]] (some geographers consider it as part of [[Northeast Asia]])\n*** [[Mongolia]] (some geographers consider it as part of [[Central Asia]] or [[Northeast Asia]])\n*** [[Northeast Asia]]\n**** [[China]]\n***** Eastern [[Inner Mongolia]]\n***** [[Northeast China]]\n**** [[Japan]] (excluding the [[Bonin Islands]] and [[Volcano Islands]])\n**** [[Korea]]\n***** [[North Korea]]\n***** [[South Korea]]\n**** [[Russia]]\n***** [[Outer Manchuria]] (also part of [[North Asia]])\n***** [[Sakhalin]] (also part of [[North Asia]])\n** [[North Asia]] (aka [[Siberia]])\n*** [[Russian Far East]]\n**** [[Outer Manchuria]] (also part of [[Northeast Asia]])\n**** [[Sakhalin]] (also part of [[Northeast Asia]])\n** [[South Asia]]\n*** [[Eastern South Asia]]\n*** [[India]]\n**** [[Central India]]\n**** [[East India]]\n**** [[Northeast India]]\n**** [[North India]]\n**** [[South India]] (aka [[South India|Peninsular India]])\n**** [[Western India]]\n*** [[List of sovereign states and dependent territories in the Indian Ocean]]\n** [[Southeast Asia]]\n*** [[Mainland Southeast Asia]] (aka [[Mainland Southeast Asia|Indochina]])\n**** [[Malay Peninsula]]\n***** [[Peninsular Malaysia]]\n***** [[Southern Thailand]]\n*** [[Maritime Southeast Asia]]\n**** [[Nusantara]]\n***** [[Borneo]]\n****** [[Brunei]]\n****** [[East Malaysia]]\n******* [[Sabah]]\n******* [[Sarawak]]\n***** [[Western New Guinea]]\n****** [[Papua (province)|Papua]]\n****** [[West Papua (province)|West Papua]]\n** [[Western Asia]] (aka [[Western Asia|Southwest Asia]])\n*** [[Anatolia|Asia Minor]] (aka [[Anatolia]])\n*** [[Arabian Peninsula|Arabia]]\n*** [[Caucasus]]\n**** [[North Caucasus]]\n**** [[Transcaucasia|South Caucasus]] (aka [[Transcaucasia]])\n\n* ''by physiography:''\n** [[Arabian Peninsula]] \n** [[Deccan Plateau]]\n** [[Eurasian Steppe]]\n** [[Indian subcontinent]]\n** [[Mainland Southeast Asia|Indochinese Peninsula]]\n** [[Indo-Gangetic Plain]]\n** [[Indus River|Indus Valley]]\n** [[Iranian Plateau]]\n** [[Korean Peninsula]]\n** [[Levant]]\n*** [[Mesopotamia]]\n** [[Malay Archipelago]]\n** [[Caucasus Mountains]]\n** [[Himalayas]]\n\n* ''by geopolitics:''\n** [[Asia-Pacific]] (APAC)\n*** [[Far East]]\n**** [[Farther India]]\n**** [[Greater China]]\n***** [[China proper]]\n**** [[Korea]]\n**** [[Russian Far East]]\n** [[Greater Middle East]]\n*** [[MENASA]]\n**** [[Indian subcontinent]]\n**** [[MENA]]\n***** [[Middle East]] (aka the [[Near East]])\n****** [[Arab League]] (aka the [[member states of the Arab League|Arab states]])\n******* [[Arabian Peninsula|Arabia]] (the [[Arabian Peninsula]])\n*** The [[Soviet Central Asia|'stans]]\n\n* ''by economics:''\n** [[Arab League]]\n** [[Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation]] (APEC)\n** [[Association of Southeast Asian Nations]] (ASEAN)\n** [[Eurasian Economic Community]]\n** [[Greater Mekong Subregion]]\n\n* ''by culture:''\n** [[Eastern world]]\n*** [[East Asian cultural sphere]]\n**** [[Greater China]]\n***** [[China proper]]\n****** [[Northern and southern China]]\n***** [[Manchuria]]\n***** [[Mongolian Plateau]]\n***** [[Tibet]]\n***** [[Xinjiang]]\n****** [[Dzungaria]]\n****** [[Tarim Basin]]\n**** [[Korea]]\n**** [[Nanyang (region)|Nanyang]]\n*** [[Greater India]] (aka the [[East Indies]])\n**** [[Farther India]]\n***** [[Malay world]]\n****** [[Greater Indonesia]]\n******* [[Nusantara]]\n**** [[Indian subcontinent]]\n** [[Muslim world]] (aka the [[Muslim world|Islamic world]])\n*** [[Arab world]]\n\n* ''by religion:''\n** [[Abrahamic religions]] ([[Abrahamic religions|Western Asian religions]] or [[Western religions]])\n** [[Eastern religions]]\n*** [[Indian religions|Dharmic religions]] ([[Indian religions]])\n*** [[East Asian religions|Taoic religions]] ([[East Asian religions]] or [[East Asian religions|Far Eastern religions]])\n\n* ''by biogeography:''\n** [[Malesia]]\n\n===== [[Europe]] =====\n* ''by the United Nations Statistics Division's geoscheme (see also: [[United Nations geoscheme for Europe|UN geoscheme for Europe]]):''\n** [[Eastern Europe]] \u2013 the UN includes [[North Asia]] ([[Siberia]]) and part of [[Central Europe]] ([[Czech Republic|Czechia]], [[Hungary]], [[Poland]] and [[Slovakia]]) in this subregion\n** [[Northern Europe]] \u2013 the UN includes the [[British Isles]] and the [[Baltic states]] in this subregion\n** [[Southern Europe]] \u2013 the UN includes [[Slovenia]] ([[Central Europe]]) in this subregion\n** [[Western Europe]] \u2013 the UN includes part of [[Central Europe]] (the [[Geographical distribution of German speakers#DACH countries|DACH]] countries and [[Liechtenstein]]) in this subregion\n\n* ''by geography:''\n** [[Central and Eastern Europe]]\n** [[Central Europe]]\n** [[Eastern Europe]]\n** [[Baltic region|Northeastern Europe]]\n** [[Northern Europe]]\n*** [[Scandinavia]]\n** [[Northwestern Europe]]\n** [[Southern Europe]]\n*** [[Southeast Europe|Southeastern Europe]] (aka the [[Balkans]])\n*** [[Iberian Peninsula|Southwestern Europe]] (aka [[Iberian Peninsula|Iberia]])\n** [[:de:Westmitteleuropa|West-Central Europe]] {{in lang|de}}\n** [[Western Europe]]\n\n* ''by physiography:''\n** [[Balkans|Balkan Peninsula]]\n** [[British Isles]]\n*** [[Great Britain]]\n*** [[Hebrides]]\n*** [[Ireland]]\n*** [[Isle of Man]]\n*** [[Isle of Wight]]\n** [[Caucasus]]\n*** [[North Caucasus]]\n*** [[Transcaucasia|South Caucasus]] (aka [[Transcaucasia]])\n** [[Channel Islands]]\n*** [[Bailiwick of Guernsey|Guernsey]]\n*** [[Jersey]]\n** [[Eurasian Steppe]]\n** [[Fennoscandia|Fennoscandian Peninsula]]\n*** [[Kola Peninsula]]\n*** [[Scandinavian Peninsula]]\n** [[European Plain|Great European Plain]]\n*** [[East European Plain]]\n** [[Iberian Peninsula]]\n** [[Italian Peninsula]] (aka the [[Italian Peninsula|Apennine Peninsula]])\n** [[Mediterranean Basin]]\n\n* ''by geology:''\n** [[Alpine orogeny]]\n** [[East European craton]]\n*** [[Baltic Shield]]\n*** [[Ukrainian Shield]]\n\n* ''by geopolitics:''\n** [[East-Central Europe]]\n** [[Post-Soviet states]]\n*** [[Baltic states]]\n*** [[Commonwealth of Independent States]]\n** [[Western world]]\n*** [[European Union]]\n*** [[NATO]]\n\n* ''by economics:''\n** [[Central European Free Trade Agreement]]\n** [[Commonwealth of Independent States Free Trade Area]] (CISFTA)\n** [[Customs Union of Belarus, Kazakhstan and Russia]]\n** [[Eurasian Economic Community]]\n** [[European Economic Area]]\n** [[European Free Trade Association]]\n** [[European Union Customs Union]]\n** [[Eurozone]]\n** [[Mediterranean Basin|Mediterranean Region]]\n** [[North Sea Region]]\n\n* ''by culture:''\n** [[Balkans]]\n*** [[Balkans|Eastern Balkans]]\n*** [[Balkans|Western Balkans]]\n** [[Baltic states]]\n** [[Benelux]]\n*** [[Belgium]]\n*** [[Netherlands]]\n*** [[Luxembourg]]\n** [[Mediterranean Basin|Mediterranean Region]]\n** [[Nordic countries]]\n** [[North Sea Region]]\n** [[S\u00e1pmi]], since 1809 divided between [[Finland]] and [[Sweden]]\n** [[Scandinavia]]\n** [[Visegr\u00e1d Group]]\n\n* ''by language:''\n** [[Germanic-speaking Europe]]\n*** [[List of territorial entities where German is an official language|DACH]]\n**** [[Germany]] ([[Germany|Deutschland]])\n**** [[Austria]]\n**** [[Switzerland]] ([[Switzerland|Confoederatio Helvetica]])\n** [[Languages of Europe#Romance|Romance-speaking Europe]] (aka [[Languages of Europe#Romance|Latin Europe]])\n** [[Slavic languages#Branches|Slavic-speaking Europe]]\n\n* ''by religion:''\n** [[Eastern religions]]\n*** [[Indian religions]]\n**** [[Buddhism in Europe]] ([[Kalmykia]])\n** [[Western religions]] ([[Abrahamic religions]] or [[Abrahamic religions|Western Asian religions]])\n*** [[Christianity]]\n**** [[Catholic Church]]\n**** [[Eastern Orthodox Church]]\n**** [[Protestantism]]\n*** [[Islam in Europe]]\n\n* ''by historical division:''\n** [[Celts|Celtic tribes]]\n** [[East\u2013West Schism]]\n*** [[Catholic Church]]\n*** [[Eastern Orthodox Church]]\n** [[Germanic peoples|Germanic tribes]]\n** [[Greco-Roman world]]\n*** [[Hellenistic period|Hellenistic world]]\n*** [[Roman Empire]]\n**** [[Eastern Roman Empire]]\n**** [[Western Roman Empire]]\n** [[Iranian peoples|Iranian tribes]]\n** [[Iron Curtain]]\n*** [[Eastern Bloc]]\n*** [[Western Bloc]]\n** [[Reformation]] ([[Protestantism]])\n** [[Slavs|Slavic tribes]]\n** [[Turkic peoples|Turkic tribes]]\n\n=== [[Americas]] ===\n{{See also|Americas (terminology)}}\n\n* ''by the United Nations Statistics Division's geoscheme (see also: [[United Nations geoscheme for the Americas|UN geoscheme for the Americas]]):''\n** [[Latin America]] and the [[Caribbean]]     \n*** [[Caribbean]]<ref name=subreg>These three subregions together form the [[continent]] of [[North America]].</ref> \u2013 the UN includes the [[Lucayan Archipelago]] in this subregion\n*** [[Latin America]]\n**** [[Central America]]<ref name=subreg /> \u2013 the UN includes [[Clipperton Island]] and [[Mexico]] in this subregion\n**** [[South America]]\n** [[Northern America]]<ref name=subreg />\n\n* ''by culture:''\n** [[Anglo-America]]\n** [[French America]]\n** [[Latin America]]\n*** [[Ibero-America]]\n**** [[Hispanic America]]\n***** [[Mesoamerica]]\n**** [[Portuguese colonization of the Americas|Portuguese America]]\n\n==== [[North America]] ====\n* ''by geography:''\n** [[Middle America (Americas)|Middle America]]\n*** [[Central America]]\n*** [[Clipperton Island]]\n*** [[Mexico]]\n*** [[West Indies]]\n**** [[Caribbean]]\n***** [[Antilles]]\n****** [[Greater Antilles]]\n******* [[Hispaniola]]\n****** [[Lesser Antilles]]\n******* [[Leeward Islands]]\n******** [[SSS Islands]]\n******* [[Southern Caribbean]]\n******** [[Leeward Antilles]]\n********* [[ABC Islands (Leeward Antilles)|ABC Islands]]\n******** [[Windward Islands]]\n***** [[Bajo Nuevo Bank]]\n***** [[Archipelago of San Andr\u00e9s, Providencia and Santa Catalina|San Andr\u00e9s and Providencia]]\n***** [[Serranilla Bank]]\n**** [[Lucayan Archipelago]]\n** [[Northern America]]\n*** [[Bermuda]]\n*** [[Canada]]\n**** [[Eastern Canada]]\n***** [[Atlantic Canada]]\n****** [[The Maritimes]]\n***** [[Central Canada]]\n**** [[Northern Canada]]\n***** [[Arctic Archipelago|Canadian Arctic Archipelago]]\n**** [[Western Canada]]\n***** [[Canadian Prairies]]\n***** [[British Columbia|West Coast]]\n*** [[Greenland]]\n*** [[Saint Pierre and Miquelon]]\n*** [[United States]]\n**** [[Alaska]]\n**** [[Contiguous United States]]\n***** [[Central United States]]\n****** [[Midwestern United States]]\n***** [[Eastern United States]]\n****** [[Northeastern United States]]\n****** [[Southeastern United States]]\n***** [[Northern United States]]\n****** [[Great Lakes region]] (including [[Ontario]], [[Canada]])\n***** [[Southern United States]]\n****** [[South Central United States]]\n***** [[Western United States]]\n****** [[Northwestern United States]]\n****** [[Southwestern United States]]\n\n* ''by physiography:''\n** [[Atlantic coastal plain]]\n** [[Atlantic Seaboard Fall Line]]\n** [[East Coast of the United States]]\n** [[Great Basin]]\n** [[Great Basin Desert]]\n** [[Great Lakes]]\n** [[Great Lakes Basin]]\n** [[Great Plains]]\n** [[Piedmont (United States)|Piedmont]]\n** [[West Coast of the United States]]\n\n* ''by geopolitics:''\n** [[Dutch Caribbean]]\n*** [[Caribbean Netherlands]] (aka the [[Caribbean Netherlands|BES Islands]])\n** [[Organisation of Eastern Caribbean States]]\n** [[Virgin Islands]]\n*** [[British Virgin Islands]]\n*** [[Spanish Virgin Islands]]\n*** [[United States Virgin Islands]]\n** [[Western Caribbean Zone]]\n\n* ''by economics:''\n** [[Caribbean Community|Caribbean Community (CARICOM)]]\n** [[Central America Free Trade Agreement|Central America Free Trade Agreement (CAFTA)]]\n** [[Great Lakes Megalopolis]]\n** [[Mesoamerican region]]\n** [[North American Free Trade Agreement|North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA)]]\n** [[Northeast megalopolis]]\n** [[Organisation of Eastern Caribbean States]]\n** [[Petrocaribe]]\n\n* ''by geology:''\n** [[Canadian Shield]]\n** [[North American craton]]\n** [[Slave craton]]\n** [[Superior craton]]\n** [[Wyoming craton]]\n\n==== [[South America]] ====\n* ''by geography:''\n** [[Altiplano]]\n** [[Amazon Basin]]\n** [[Andean states]]\n** [[Andes]]\n** [[Brazilian Highlands]]\n** [[Caribbean South America]]\n** [[Gran Chaco]]\n** [[The Guianas|Guianan states]]\n** [[Pampa]]\n** [[Pantanal]]\n** [[Patagonia]]\n** [[Southern Cone]]\n\n* ''by economics:''\n** [[Andean Community]]\n** [[Mercosur]]\n** [[Union of South American Nations]]\n\n* ''by geology:'' \n** [[Guiana Shield]]\n\n=== [[Antarctica]] ===\n* ''by the United Nations Statistics Division's geoscheme:''\n** [[Antarctica]]\n\n* ''by geography:''\n** [[List of Antarctic and subantarctic islands|Antarctic and subantarctic islands]]\n*** [[Bouvet Island]] (some geographers consider it as part of [[Africa]])\n*** [[French Southern and Antarctic Lands]] (some geographers consider them as part of [[Africa]])\n*** [[Heard Island and McDonald Islands]] (some geographers consider them as part of [[Africa]])\n*** [[Macquarie Island]] (some geographers consider it as part of [[Oceania]])\n*** [[New Zealand Subantarctic Islands]] (some geographers consider them as part of [[Oceania]])\n*** [[Peter I Island]]\n*** [[Prince Edward Islands]] (some geographers consider them as part of [[Africa]])\n*** [[South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands]] (some geographers consider them as part of [[South America]])\n*** [[South Orkney Islands]]\n*** [[South Shetland Islands]]\n** [[Antarctica|Mainland Antarctica]]\n*** [[Antarctic Peninsula]]\n*** [[East Antarctica]]\n*** [[Transantarctic Mountains]]\n*** [[West Antarctica]]\n\n=== [[Oceania]] ===\n* ''by the United Nations Statistics Division's geoscheme (see also: [[United Nations geoscheme for Oceania|UN geoscheme for Oceania]]):''\n** [[Australia]] and [[New Zealand]] \u2013 the UN includes the [[Elizabeth Reef|Elizabeth]] and [[Middleton Reef|Middleton Reefs]], [[Lord Howe Island|Lord Howe Island Group]] and [[Norfolk Island]] in this subregion\n** [[Melanesia]] \u2013 the UN includes [[New Caledonia]] and [[New Guinea]] in this subregion\n** [[Micronesia]]\n** [[Polynesia]] \u2013 the UN excludes [[New Zealand]] from this subregion\n\n* ''by geography:''\n** [[Australasia]]\n*** [[Australia (continent)]]\n**** [[Australia]]\n***** [[Ashmore and Cartier Islands]] (some geographers consider them as part of [[Southeast Asia]])\n***** [[Australian Capital Territory]]\n***** [[Christmas Island]] (some geographers consider it as part of [[Southeast Asia]])\n***** [[Cocos (Keeling) Islands]] (some geographers consider them as part of [[Southeast Asia]])\n***** [[Coral Sea Islands|Coral Sea Islands Territory]] (excluding the [[Elizabeth Reef|Elizabeth]] and [[Middleton Reef|Middleton Reefs]])\n***** [[Jervis Bay Territory]]\n***** [[New South Wales]] (excluding the [[Lord Howe Island|Lord Howe Island Group]])\n***** [[Northern Territory]]\n***** [[Queensland]]\n***** [[South Australia]]\n***** [[Tasmania]]\n***** [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]]\n***** [[Western Australia]]\n**** [[New Guinea]] (some geographers consider it as part of [[Melanesia]])\n***** [[Papua New Guinea]]\n***** [[Western New Guinea]]\n****** [[Papua (province)|Papua]]\n****** [[West Papua (province)|West Papua]]\n*** [[Zealandia]]\n**** [[Elizabeth Reef|Elizabeth]] and [[Middleton Reef|Middleton Reefs]]\n**** [[Lord Howe Island|Lord Howe Island Group]]\n**** [[New Caledonia]] (also part of [[Melanesia]])\n**** [[New Zealand]] (excluding the [[Kermadec Islands]], some geographers consider it as part of [[Polynesia]])\n**** [[Norfolk Island]]\n** [[List of islands in the Pacific Ocean|Pacific Islands]]\n*** [[Melanesia]] (some geographers consider it as part of [[Australasia]])\n*** [[Micronesia]] (including the [[Bonin Islands]] and [[Volcano Islands]])\n*** [[Polynesia]] (including [[Easter Island]], [[Hawaii]], the [[Kermadec Islands]] and [[Isla Salas y G\u00f3mez|Salas y G\u00f3mez Island]])\n\n* ''by geology (see also: [[Geology of Australia]]):''\n** [[Archean|Archaean]]\n** [[Australian Shield]]\n** [[Centralian Superbasin]]\n** [[Gawler Craton]]\n** [[Narryer gneiss]]\n** [[Ore genesis]]\n** [[Perth Basin]]\n** [[Pilbara Craton]]\n** [[Western Plateau]]\n** [[Yilgarn Craton]]\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Autonomous area#Autonomous region|Autonomous region]]\n* [[Committee of the Regions]]\n* [[Continent]]\n* [[Continental fragment]]\n* [[Euroregion]]\n* [[Latin names of regions]]\n* [[Military district]]\n* [[Polar region]]\n* [[Region]]\n* [[Regional district]]\n* [[Regional municipality]]\n* [[Subcontinent]]\n* [[Submerged continents]]\n* [[Supercontinent]]\n* [[United Nations geoscheme]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://unstats.un.org/unsd/geoinfo/ungegn.htm UN Group of Experts on Geographical Names]\n* [http://unstats.un.org/unsd/methods/m49/m49regin.htm UN Statistics Division's Country and Area Codes Classifications]\n\n{{Continents of the world}}\n{{Regions of the world}}\n\n[[Category:Administrative territorial entities by type]]\n", "name_user": "Kenwick", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Subregion"}
{"title_page": "Richard Zeckhauser", "text_new": "{{Infobox economist\n| name             = Richard J. Zeckhauser\n| image       = Richard Zeckhauser (2014).jpg\n| image_size       =\n| caption    = Richard Zeckhauser (2014)\n| birth_date       = 1940\n| birth_place      = \n| death_date       =\n| death_place      =\n| nationality      = American\n| institution      = [[Harvard University]]\n| field            = [[Decision theory]], [[game theory]], [[behavioral economics]]\n| school_tradition = Decision theory, behavioral economics\n| alma_mater       = [[Harvard University]]\n| influences       = [[Thomas Schelling]]\n| doctoral_students= [[Nat Keohane]], [[Gernot Wagner]]\n| contributions    = \n| awards           = \n| signature        = <!-- file name only -->\n| spouse           = Sally H. Zeckhauser<ref name=\"sallyref\" />\n| repec_prefix = e | repec_id = pze7\n}}\n'''Richard Jay Zeckhauser''' (born 1940) is an American [[economist]] and the [[Frank P. Ramsey]] Professor of [[Political Economy]] at the [[Kennedy School of Government]] at [[Harvard University]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.environment.harvard.edu/about/faculty/richard-zeckhauser | title=Richard Zeckhauser| date=2009-10-12}}</ref>\n\nHe holds a [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] (''[[summa cum laude]]'') and a PhD in [[economics]] from [[Harvard University]]. Early in his career, he was one of the \"[[Whiz Kids (Department of Defense)|whiz kids]]\" assembled by Defense Secretary [[Robert S. McNamara]] to apply cutting-edge analysis to [[Cold War]] military strategy. He is married to Sally H. Zeckhauser.<ref name=\"sallyref\">{{cite news|title='Quiet' Harvard Leader To Retire {{!}} News {{!}} The Harvard Crimson|url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/2009/3/10/quiet-harvard-leader-to-retire-harvards/|work=www.thecrimson.com|language=en}}</ref>\n\nHe is the author or co-author of many books and over 300 peer-reviewed articles. His most significant works focus on risk management, decision sciences, investment, and policy-making under uncertainty. Zeckhauser introduced the term \"ignorance\" into decision-making under uncertainty, as in: there's \"risk\", \"uncertainty\", and outright \"ignorance\".<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Zeckhauser|first1=Richard|title=Investing in the Unknown and Unknowable|journal=Journal of Risk and Uncertainty|date=11 January 2011|doi=10.2470/rf.v2010.n2.7|url=https://www.cfapubs.org/doi/abs/10.2470/rf.v2010.n2.7|language=EN|doi-broken-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\nHis most recent book, with Peter Schuck, is ''Targeting in Social Programs.'' The book examines how and why to deploy scarce public resources to solve public problems. While he holds no formal office, he has long been an informal leader at the Kennedy School and at Harvard.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YbDDXznHPI0</ref> He is also a consultant with Analysis Group.<ref>http://www.analysisgroup.com/richard_zeckhauser.aspx</ref> In 1994, he was elected to the [[Common Cause]] National Governing Board.\n\n==Bridge career==\nZeckhauser is a champion [[Contract bridge|bridge]] player.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Alexander|first1=Sophie|title=KSG Prof Plays His Cards Right {{!}} News {{!}} The Harvard Crimson|url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/2007/3/19/ksg-prof-plays-his-cards-right/|work=www.thecrimson.com|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Wins===\n* [[North American Bridge Championships]] (2)\n** [[Blue Ribbon Pairs]] (1) 1966\n** [[Rockwell Mixed Pairs|Mixed Pairs]] (1) 2007\n\n===Runners-up===\n* [[North American Bridge Championships]] (2)\n** [[Mitchell Board-a-Match Teams|Men's Board-a-Match Teams]] (1) 1968\n** [[Chicago Mixed Board-a-Match|Mixed Board-a-Match Teams]] (2) 2003, 2012\n\n==Significant works==\n* [[Lawrence Summers|Summers, Lawrence]], and Richard Zeckhauser. \"Policymaking for posterity.\" Journal of Risk and Uncertainty 37.2-3 (2008): 115\u2013140.\n* Zeckhauser, Richard. \"[https://www.cfapubs.org/doi/abs/10.2470/rf.v2010.n2.7 Investing in the Unknown and Unknowable].\" (2010): 77\u2013117.\n* Samuelson, William, and Richard Zeckhauser. \"[https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/BF00055564 Status quo bias in decision making].\" Journal of risk and uncertainty 1, no. 1 (1988): 7\u201359.\n* Zeckhauser, Richard (2006) [http://www.bepress.com/cas/vol1/iss2/art5/ \"Investing in the Unknown and Unknowable\"], ''Capitalism and Society'': Vol. 1 : Iss. 2, Article 5. {{doi|10.2202/1932-0213.1009}}\n* Schuck, Peter H. &  Zeckhauser, Richard J. ''Targeting in Social Programs: Avoiding Bad Bets, Removing Bad Apples'', Brookings Institution Press, 2010, {{ISBN|978-0-8157-0428-7}}\n* Zeckhauser, Richard, [https://books.google.com/books?id=YsapejLQstkC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Richard+Zeckhauser&hl=en&ei=dHxbTKa3FIT78AaryNj4AQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CC0Q6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Strategy and choice''], MIT Press, 1991, {{ISBN|978-0-262-24033-8}}\n* Zeckhauser, Richard, Keeney, Ralph L., Sebenius, James K. [https://books.google.com/books?id=i-L0EGtVnG4C&printsec=frontcover&dq=Richard+Zeckhauser&hl=en&ei=5HxbTK27JsP98AbznviDDw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=5&ved=0CEIQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Wise choices: decisions, games, and negotiations''], Harvard Business Press, 1996, {{ISBN|978-0-87584-677-4}}\n* {{cite encyclopedia |last1= Zeckhauser |first1=Richard  |editor= [[David R. Henderson]]|encyclopedia=[[Concise Encyclopedia of Economics]] |title=Insurance |url=http://www.econlib.org/library/Enc/Insurance.html |year=2008 |edition= 2nd |publisher=[[Library of Economics and Liberty]] |location=Indianapolis |isbn=978-0865976658 |oclc=237794267}}\n\n==Trivia==\nZeckhauser is connected to the so-called [[Yhprum's law]], the opposite of [[Murphy's law]], saying: \"Sometimes systems that should not work, work nevertheless.\" <ref>{{cite journal|last=Resnick|first=Paul|author2=Zeckhauser, Richard |author3=Swanson, John |author4= Lockwood, Kate |title=The value of reputation on eBay: A controlled experiment|journal=Experimental Economics|date=June 2006|volume=9|issue=2|pages=79\u2013101|doi=10.1007/s10683-006-4309-2|url=http://www.hks.harvard.edu/fs/rzeckhau/postcards.pdf}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://sites.hks.harvard.edu/fs/rzeckhau/ Official website]\n* [https://www.nber.org/authors/richard_zeckhauser NBER Publications by Richard J. Zeckhauser]\n* {{LCAuth|n82080130|Richard Zeckhauser|25|}} (including 2 as second author 'Richard J.')\n* {{WBFpeople}}\n* [[Common Cause]]\n{{WPCBIndex}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zeckhauser, Richard}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:Date of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:John F. Kennedy School of Government faculty]]\n[[Category:21st-century American economists]]\n[[Category:Health economists]]\n[[Category:American contract bridge players]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Negotiation scholars]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Econometric Society]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences]]\n[[Category:Distinguished Fellows of the American Economic Association]]\n[[Category:National Bureau of Economic Research]]\n\n\n{{US-economist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox economist\n| name             = Richard J. Zeckhauser\n| image       = Richard Zeckhauser (2014).jpg\n| image_size       =\n| caption    = Richard Zeckhauser (2014)\n| birth_date       = 1940\n| birth_place      = \n| death_date       =\n| death_place      =\n| nationality      = American\n| institution      = [[Harvard University]]\n| field            = [[Decision theory]], [[game theory]], [[behavioral economics]]\n| school_tradition = Decision theory, behavioral economics\n| alma_mater       = [[Harvard University]]\n| influences       = [[Thomas Schelling]]\n| doctoral_students= [[Nat Keohane]], [[Gernot Wagner]]\n| contributions    = \n| awards           = \n| signature        = <!-- file name only -->\n| spouse           = Sally H. Zeckhauser<ref name=\"sallyref\" />\n| repec_prefix = e | repec_id = pze7\n}}\n'''Richard Jay Zeckhauser''' (born 1940) is an American [[economist]] and the [[Frank P. Ramsey]] Professor of [[Political Economy]] at the [[Kennedy School of Government]] at [[Harvard University]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.environment.harvard.edu/about/faculty/richard-zeckhauser | title=Richard Zeckhauser| date=2009-10-12}}</ref>\n\nHe holds a [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] (''[[summa cum laude]]'') and a PhD in [[economics]] from [[Harvard University]]. Early in his career, he was one of the \"[[Whiz Kids (Department of Defense)|whiz kids]]\" assembled by Defense Secretary [[Robert S. McNamara]] to apply cutting-edge analysis to [[Cold War]] military strategy. He is married to Sally H. Zeckhauser.<ref name=\"sallyref\">{{cite news|title='Quiet' Harvard Leader To Retire {{!}} News {{!}} The Harvard Crimson|url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/2009/3/10/quiet-harvard-leader-to-retire-harvards/|work=www.thecrimson.com|language=en}}</ref>\n\nHe is the author or co-author of many books and over 300 peer-reviewed articles. His most significant works focus on risk management, decision sciences, investment, and policy-making under uncertainty. Zeckhauser introduced the term \"ignorance\" into decision-making under uncertainty, as in: there's \"risk\", \"uncertainty\", and outright \"ignorance\".<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Zeckhauser|first1=Richard|title=Investing in the Unknown and Unknowable|journal=Journal of Risk and Uncertainty|date=11 January 2011|doi=10.2470/rf.v2010.n2.7|url=https://www.cfapubs.org/doi/abs/10.2470/rf.v2010.n2.7|language=EN|doi-broken-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\nHis most recent book, with Peter Schuck, is ''Targeting in Social Programs.'' The book examines how and why to deploy scarce public resources to solve public problems. While he holds no formal office, he has long been an informal leader at the Kennedy School and at Harvard.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YbDDXznHPI0</ref> He is also a consultant with Analysis Group.<ref>http://www.analysisgroup.com/richard_zeckhauser.aspx</ref> In 1994, he was elected to the [[Common Cause]] National Governing Board.\n\n==Bridge career==\nZeckhauser is a champion [[Contract bridge|bridge]] player.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Alexander|first1=Sophie|title=KSG Prof Plays His Cards Right {{!}} News {{!}} The Harvard Crimson|url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/2007/3/19/ksg-prof-plays-his-cards-right/|work=www.thecrimson.com|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Wins===\n* [[North American Bridge Championships]] (2)\n** [[Blue Ribbon Pairs]] (1) 1966\n** [[Rockwell Mixed Pairs|Mixed Pairs]] (1) 2007\n\n===Runners-up===\n* [[North American Bridge Championships]] (2)\n** [[Mitchell Board-a-Match Teams|Men's Board-a-Match Teams]] (1) 1968\n** [[Chicago Mixed Board-a-Match|Mixed Board-a-Match Teams]] (2) 2003, 2012\n\n==Significant works==\n* [[Lawrence Summers|Summers, Lawrence]], and Richard Zeckhauser. \"Policymaking for posterity.\" Journal of Risk and Uncertainty 37.2-3 (2008): 115\u2013140.\n* Zeckhauser, Richard. \"[https://www.cfapubs.org/doi/abs/10.2470/rf.v2010.n2.7 Investing in the Unknown and Unknowable].\" (2010): 77-117.\n* Samuelson, William, and Richard Zeckhauser. \"[https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/BF00055564 Status quo bias in decision making].\" Journal of risk and uncertainty 1, no. 1 (1988): 7-59.\n* Zeckhauser, Richard (2006) [http://www.bepress.com/cas/vol1/iss2/art5/ \"Investing in the Unknown and Unknowable\"], ''Capitalism and Society'': Vol. 1 : Iss. 2, Article 5. {{doi|10.2202/1932-0213.1009}}\n* Schuck, Peter H. &  Zeckhauser, Richard J. ''Targeting in Social Programs: Avoiding Bad Bets, Removing Bad Apples'', Brookings Institution Press, 2010, {{ISBN|978-0-8157-0428-7}}\n* Zeckhauser, Richard, [https://books.google.com/books?id=YsapejLQstkC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Richard+Zeckhauser&hl=en&ei=dHxbTKa3FIT78AaryNj4AQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CC0Q6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Strategy and choice''], MIT Press, 1991, {{ISBN|978-0-262-24033-8}}\n* Zeckhauser, Richard, Keeney, Ralph L., Sebenius, James K. [https://books.google.com/books?id=i-L0EGtVnG4C&printsec=frontcover&dq=Richard+Zeckhauser&hl=en&ei=5HxbTK27JsP98AbznviDDw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=5&ved=0CEIQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Wise choices: decisions, games, and negotiations''], Harvard Business Press, 1996, {{ISBN|978-0-87584-677-4}}\n* {{cite encyclopedia |last1= Zeckhauser |first1=Richard  |editor= [[David R. Henderson]]|encyclopedia=[[Concise Encyclopedia of Economics]] |title=Insurance |url=http://www.econlib.org/library/Enc/Insurance.html |year=2008 |edition= 2nd |publisher=[[Library of Economics and Liberty]] |location=Indianapolis |isbn=978-0865976658 |oclc=237794267}}\n\n==Trivia==\nZeckhauser is connected to the so-called [[Yhprum's law]], the opposite of [[Murphy's law]], saying: \"Sometimes systems that should not work, work nevertheless.\" <ref>{{cite journal|last=Resnick|first=Paul|author2=Zeckhauser, Richard |author3=Swanson, John |author4= Lockwood, Kate |title=The value of reputation on eBay: A controlled experiment|journal=Experimental Economics|date=June 2006|volume=9|issue=2|pages=79\u2013101|doi=10.1007/s10683-006-4309-2|url=http://www.hks.harvard.edu/fs/rzeckhau/postcards.pdf}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://sites.hks.harvard.edu/fs/rzeckhau/ Official website]\n* [https://www.nber.org/authors/richard_zeckhauser NBER Publications by Richard J. Zeckhauser]\n* {{LCAuth|n82080130|Richard Zeckhauser|25|}} (including 2 as second author 'Richard J.')\n* {{WBFpeople}}\n* [[Common Cause]]\n{{WPCBIndex}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zeckhauser, Richard}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:Date of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:John F. Kennedy School of Government faculty]]\n[[Category:21st-century American economists]]\n[[Category:Health economists]]\n[[Category:American contract bridge players]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Negotiation scholars]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Econometric Society]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences]]\n[[Category:Distinguished Fellows of the American Economic Association]]\n[[Category:National Bureau of Economic Research]]\n\n\n{{US-economist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Invertiert", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSignificant works", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Zeckhauser"}
{"title_page": "Paul Cayard", "text_new": "{{use mdy dates|date=November 2013}}\n{{Infobox sailor\n| name = Paul Cayard\n| image = Paul-Cayard.jpg\n| imagesize =\n| caption = \n| fullname = Paul Pierre Cayard\n| nicknames =\n| nationality = [[United States|American]]\n| classes = [[Star (sailboat)|Star]]\n| club = \n| collegeteam = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1959|05|19|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[San Francisco]], [[California]], USA\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| height = \n| weight = \n| retired = \n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalCompetition|World Championships}}\n{{MedalGold|[[Star World Championships|1988 Buenos Aires]]|Star class}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[Star World Championships|1984 Vilamoura]]|Star class}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[Star World Championships|1985 Nassau]]|Star class}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[Star World Championships|1987 Chicago]]|Star class}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[Star World Championships|1992 San Francisco]]|Star class}}\n}}\n\n'''Paul Pierre Cayard''' (born May 19, 1959) is an American [[yacht]]sman and professional sailor.   He has competed at multiple world championship level [[sailing (sport)|sailing]] events, including the [[America's Cup]], the [[Whitbread Round the World Race]],the [[Volvo Ocean Race]] and the [[Olympic Games]]. In 1998 he was selected as the [[US Sailor of the Year Awards|US Rolex Yachtsmen of the Year]]. He has won seven world championships, twice participated in the Olympic Games and seven times in the America's Cup.   In 2002 he was elected into the Sailing World Hall of Fame.\n\n==Biography==\nPaul Cayard was born in [[San Francisco]], [[California]].  He began sailing in 1967 at the age of eight.  He graduated in 1981 with a degree in business management from [[San Francisco State University]].   He speaks three languages: [[English language|English]], [[French language|French]] and [[Italian language|Italian]].  He enjoys flying and holds a [[Pilot certification in the United States|pilots certification]] for single engine aircraft.  Of all his sailing accomplishments, he counts his 1988 Star Class world championship as his most prized victory.<ref name=Cayard>{{cite web|url=http://www.cayardsailing.com/cs_PaulCayard.cfm|title=Paul Cayard Profile|work=Cayard Sailing|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100601092853/http://www.cayardsailing.com/cs_PaulCayard.cfm|archivedate=June 1, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nCayard is a member of four different yacht clubs,  the St. Francis Yacht Club,  the San Francisco Yacht Club, the Encinal Yacht Club, and the Yacht Club de Monaco.<ref name=Cayard/>\n\nFor the 34th America's Cup in San Francisco, Paul Cayard was the CEO of [[Team Artemis|Artemis Racing]].<ref>http://www.sailingworld.com/blogs/racing/americas-cup/complexity-squared</ref>\n\n== Sailing career ==\nFrom an early age Cayard showed great promise as a sailor, and by his early teens was successfully sailing high performance dinghies such as the [[505 (dinghy)|International 505]] and Laser. As Cayard grew and became more proficient in sailing, he gained the notice of [[Tom Blackaller]], who invited Cayard to crew for him on his [[Star (sailboat)|Star class]] sailboat.  Blackaller would become an influential mentor, and the Star Class would become a lifelong passion for Cayard.\n\nIn 1984, Cayard was selected as an alternate in the [[Olympic Games]] for the USA sailing team.  Sailing in the Star Class, he won the silver medal at the pre-Olympic regatta in 2003, going on to finish 5th at the 2004 Summer Olympic Games in [[Athens]].\n\nCayard has competed in a broad range of ocean racing events with an impressive record. He has won the 1994 [[Kenwood Cup]], the 1994 and 1996 [[Sardinia Cup]], and the 1995 [[Admirals Cup]]. His top achievement in this arena was becoming the first American to win the [[Volvo Ocean Race|Whitbread Round the World]] in 1997/1998 as skipper of [[EF Language]]. He beat out ten other yachts for the prize over a course of 32,000 miles (51,500&nbsp;km).\n\nAs of 2006, Cayard competed in the Volvo Ocean Race as skipper of ''Pirates of the Caribbean'' syndicate sponsored by [[The Walt Disney Company]] in reference to the movie of the same name. Cayard Sailing, Inc. managed the syndicate.  The team won the final leg into Gothenburg and finished the overall race in 2nd place.\n\nIn 2007, Paul Cayard and Russell Coutts announced the launch of the World Sailing League in partnership with internationally renowned Portuguese sports promoter, Jo\u00e3o Lagos. The World Sailing League (WSL) will be held at premier sailing locations around the world with the series winner receiving $2 million in prize money.\n\nIn 2009, Cayard joined [[Artemis Racing]], owned by [[Torbj\u00f6rn T\u00f6rnqvist]].  Cayard was the Skipper of the Louis Vuitton Trophy team and Tactician onboard TP52 Artemis (www.artemisracing.com).  \n[[Artemis Racing]] became the Challenger of Record in the [[34th America's Cup]] in 2010 and Cayard became CEO.\n\n=== America's Cup ===\nCayard's first [[America's Cup]] was in 1983 aboard [[Tom Blackaller|Tom Blackaller's]] ''Defender'' as a jib trimmer. ''Defender'' finished third in the defender selection series. For the [[1987 America's Cup]] series, Cayard moved up to tactician and alternate helmsman on Blackaller's new boat ''USA'', which lost out to [[Dennis Conner]]'s ''Stars & Stripes'' for the right to challenge for the cup.<ref>[http://www.americaone.org/cup/history7.html History of the America\u2019s Cup - The Cup Down Under]</ref>\n\nFor the [[1992 America's Cup]], Cayard became manager and skipper of ''[[Il Moro di Venezia]]'' from Italy, a syndicate backed by [[Raul Gardini]]. In 1991, he won the first ever [[International America's Cup Class]] world championship. Over the months long challenger selection series, Cayard's team beat out seven other teams from six other countries to win the [[1992 Louis Vuitton Cup]] and gain the right to challenge for the America's Cup. Part of the challenge included protests where Cayard successfully protested the employment of a bowsprit on the [[Team New Zealand|New Zealand challenge]].\n\nThough ''Il Moro di Venezia'' was outclassed in the America's Cup races by the faster ''[[America\u00b3]]'', Cayard's expertise in sailing provided some memorable moments. In the second race of the series, his yacht won the start and maintained a small lead for the entire race. He employed classic match racing tactics throughout the race, and at the downwind finish managed to beat ''America\u00b3'' by three seconds, producing what was at the time the smallest winning margin in cup history. Cayard went on to lose this series 4-1.\n\nIn 1995, Cayard rejoined an American effort for the America's Cup, joining Team Dennis Conner aboard ''[[Stars & Stripes (yacht)|Stars & Stripes]]'' as primary helmsman. Though ''Stars & Stripes'' was noticeably slower than other boats on the defender series, the syndicate managed to win the [[1995 Citizen Cup]] for the right to defend the Cup. In an unprecedented move, Team Dennis Conner decided to use the faster yacht ''[[List of IACC yachts|Young America]]'' from the PACT 95 syndicate to defend the Cup. Cayard and this syndicate ended up losing the Cup 5-0 to [[Team New Zealand]], who had won the [[1995 Louis Vuitton Cup]].\n\nWith the change in venue and hemisphere for the Cup, the next America's Cup was not held until 2000. For the [[2000 America's Cup]], Cayard formed his own syndicate with backing from a number of sponsors and named it ''[[International America's Cup Class|AmericaOne]]''. The sponsoring yacht club was [[St. Francis Yacht Club]] of San Francisco. This syndicate competed against 14 challengers from 10 nations for the right to challenge for the Cup. ''AmericaOne'' reached the finals of the [[2000 Louis Vuitton Cup]] racing against ''Prada'' for the right to challenge against [[Team New Zealand]] for the 2000 America's Cup. The final over the best of nine races was hotly contested, with neither yacht ever winning by more than two minutes. ''Prada'' won the first race, and ''AmericaOne'' the second. ''Prada'' went on to win the next two races, putting ''AmericaOne'' at a 3-1 disadvantage. ''AmericaOne'' then proceeded to win the next three races in a row and appeared on the brink of winning the Louis Vuitton Cup. However, equipment fatigue and failure proved decisive, several spinnakers were blown out, and ''Prada'' ended up winning the next two races and the series, 5-4, earning the right to challenge for the Cup.  Prada ultimately lost in the America's Cup, 5-0 to the defender Team New Zealand.<ref>[http://www.americaone.org/cup/history8.html History of the America\u2019s Cup - Big Boats Reborn]</ref>\n\nFollowing the conclusion of the 2000 America's Cup, Cayard recommended to the ''AmericaOne'' syndicate board of trustees that the syndicate should not compete for the [[2003 America's Cup]], citing significant financial and recruiting obstacles. Assets of AmericaOne were eventually sold to [[Larry Ellison]] who founded the Oracle Racing syndicate, later joining forces with BMW Racing to form [[Oracle BMW Racing]], with Cayard as skipper. Cayard later was moved out of the skipper position into an administrative position and ultimately left the syndicate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2002/WORLD/sailing/12/11/cayard.ppl/index.html|title=Cayard Laments Oracle Move|work=CNN Inside Sailing|date=December 11, 2002}}</ref><ref>[http://www.yachtracing.com/richroberts/012903.htm Cayard: the AC From the Outside (en)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929201533/http://www.yachtracing.com/richroberts/012903.htm |date=September 29, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2007, Cayard was involved in the [[2007 America's Cup]] as Technical Advisor to Desafio Espanol 2007. Cayard also commentated on the [[2007 Louis Vuitton Cup]] and on the [[2007 America's Cup]] for [[La7]], the Italian broadcast rights holder.  On 12 October 2007, Cayard announced that he was joining [[Desafio Espanol]] as Sports Director for the 33rd America's Cup.\n\nFor the 33rd America's Cup, Cayard provided commentary for Eurosport and in 2009 joined Torbjorn Tornqvist's sailing on Artemis Racing for the TP52 and Louis Vuitton Trophy regattas. Cayard also helmed RC44 Katusha on the RC44 Championship Tour from 2010-2012.\n\n=== Achievements ===\n{{updated|27 September 2015|<ref>https://members.sailing.org/sailors/biog.php?memberid=40455</ref>}}\n{| {{AchievementTable|Event=yes|NotesOff=y}}\n|-\n| 1978 || [[Star World Championships]] || [[San Francisco]], USA || 4th || Star class\n|-\n| 1979 || [[Star World Championships]] || [[Marstrand]], Sweden || 17th || Star class\n|-\n| 1984 || [[Star World Championships]] || [[Vilamoura]], Portugal || style=\"background:#c96;\"| 3rd || Star class\n|-\n| 1985 || [[Star World Championships]] || [[Nassau, Bahamas|Nassau]], Bahamas || style=\"background:#c96;\"| 3rd || Star class\n|-\n| 1987 || [[Star World Championships]] || [[Chicago]], USA || style=\"background:#c96;\"| 3rd || Star class\n|-\n| 1988 || [[Star World Championships]] || [[Buenos Aires]], Argentina ||style=\"background:gold;\"| 1st || Star class\n|-\n| 1989 || [[Star World Championships]] || [[Porto Cervo]], Italy || 10th || Star class\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 1991 || [[IACC World Championship]]  || [[San Diego]], ||1st|| America's Cup\n|-\n| [[IOR 50 World Championship]] || [[Japan]], ||1st|| Intl. 50' Class\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 1992 || [[ISAF Open Match Racing World Championship|IYRU Match Racing World Championships]] || [[Long Beach, California|Long Beach]], USA || 5th || Match racing\n|-\n| [[Star World Championships]] || [[San Francisco]], USA || style=\"background:#c96;\"| 3rd || Star class\n|-\n| 1996 || [[Star World Championships]] || [[Rio de Janeiro]], Brazil || 4th || Star class\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 2002 || [[Star World Championships]] || [[Marina del Rey]], USA || 4th || Star class\n|-\n| [[Farr 40 World Championships]] || [[Paradise Island]], Bahamas || 6th || Farr 40 class\n|-\n| 2003 || [[ISAF Sailing World Championships]] || [[Cadiz]], Spain || 8th || Star class\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 2004 || [[Star World Championships]] || [[Gaeta]], Italy || 5th || Star class\n|-\n| Olympic Games || [[Athens]], Greece || 5th || Star class\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 2008 || [[Farr 40 World Championships]] || [[Florida]], USA || 11th || Farr 40 class\n|-\n| [[TP52 World Championships]] || [[Lanzarote]], Spain || 7th || TP52 class\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 2009 || [[505 World Championships]] || [[San Francisco]], USA || 7th || 505 class\n|-\n| [[TP52 World Championships]] || [[Palma, Majorca|Palma]], Spain || style=\"background:#c96;\"| 3rd || TP52 class\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 2010 || [[RC44 World Championships]] || [[Puerto Calero]], Spain || 4th || RC44 class\n|-\n| [[TP52 World Championships]] || [[Valencia]], Spain || 4th || TP52 class\n|}\n\n* Won the El Toro class North American championship in the under 18 category in 1975.\n* Won the Star class world championship in 1988.\n* Won the [[Maxi yacht|Maxi class]] world championship in 1988 aboard ''Il Moro di Venezia III''.\n* Won the 1989 One Ton class world championship.\n* Won the 1991 50-foot world championship aboard ''Abracadabra'' in Japan.\n* 1991 Yachting magazine Yachtsman of the Year.\n* Won the Louis Vuitton Cup in 1992.\n* 1992 [[Rothmans]] Yachtsman of the Year.\n* Won the Citizens Cup in 1995 for the right to defend the America's Cup.\n* Won 1994 and 1996 Sardinia Cup (ocean racing)\n* Won 1994 Kenwood Cup (ocean racing)\n* Won the 1995 Admiral's Cup (ocean racing)\n* Won the 1996 International Level Class 40 world championship.\n* Won the 1999 Steinlager Cup.\n* Won the 1997/98 Whitbread Round the World Race (now known as the [[Volvo Ocean Race]]) as skipper of the [[Sweden|Swedish]] entry EF Language.\n* 1998 [[Rolex]] Yachtsman of the Year.\n* Won 2002 IMS world championship in [[Capri]], Italy.\n* 2002 inductee into the Sailing World Hall of Fame.\n* 2005-2006 Skippered 'Pirates of the Caribbean' in the Volvo Ocean Race, placing 2nd overall.\n* Tactician on board John Kilroy's ''Samba Pa Ti'', winner of the [[Farr 40]] North American Championships 2004, US National Championships 2004, Pacific Coast Championships 2004, and West Coast Season Championships 2004.\n* 2010 Became CEO of Artemis Racing, Challenger of Record for the 34th America's Cup, which is backed by Torbj\u00f6rn Tornqvist. \n* 2011 Inducted into the [[National Sailing Hall of Fame]] in San Diego, CA.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nshof.org/hall-of-fame/class-of-2011-extended/78-the-national-sailing-hall-of-fame/hall-of-fame-2011/333-cayard-paul-2011-hall-of-fame|title=Paul Cayard 2011 Inductee |publisher=Nshof.org |date= |accessdate=November 22, 2019}}</ref>\n* 2012 Sailed as tactician in October ACWS event in San Francisco for Artemis Racing Red.\n* 2014 Won Miami Star Winter Series - Star Mid-Winter Championship, Miami, FL.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Italy at the America's Cup]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n* [http://www.americaone.org/syndicate/cayard.html Record of world championships won]\n* [http://www.americaone.org/results-finals.html 2000 Louis Vuitton Cup finals results]\n\n== External links ==\n* {{World Sailing|40455|USAPC5}}\n* {{IOC profile|paul-cayard}}\n* {{Olympic Channel|paul-cayard}}\n* {{SR/Olympics|ca/paul-cayard-1}}\n* [http://www.cayardsailing.com/ Cayard Sailing website]\n* [http://www.americascup.com/en/acclopaedia/circlinggalaxy/profil.php?idIndex=&idContent=4497  32nd America's Cup website]\n* {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070227084316/http://www.wsl2009.com/  |title=World Sailing League website}}\n* [http://www.blackpearlracing.com Pirates of the Caribbean entry in the Volvo Ocean Race 2005-2006 website]\n* {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070504045056/http://www.la7.it/vela/index.asp |title=LA7 Italy's website}}\n* {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070629032853/http://www.la7.it/vela/video.asp |title=Cayard's italian video}}\n* [http://www.americaone.org ''AmericaOne'' website]\n* {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110603233740/https://sports.yahoo.com/olympics/torino2006/usa/paul+cayard/1726317/ |date=June 3, 2011 |title=Yahoo! Sports profile for the 2006 Winter Olympics}}\n* {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120331213628/http://32nd.americascup.com/en/acclopaedia/boatdestiny/index.php?idIndex=0&idContent=3542 |title=History of ''Il Moro di Venezia'' at the 1992 America's Cup}}\n* {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930202429/http://www.usoc.org/26_21701.htm |title=Paul Cayard's U.S. Olympic Team bio}}\n\n{{Footer World Champions Star}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cayard, Paul}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:American male sailors (sport)]]\n[[Category:Artemis Racing sailors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Oracle Racing sailors]]\n[[Category:Il Moro Challenge sailors]]\n[[Category:Sailors at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Star]]\n[[Category:Star class world champions]]\n[[Category:US Sailor of the Year]]\n[[Category:Volvo Ocean Race sailors]]\n[[Category:1983 America's Cup sailors]]\n[[Category:1987 America's Cup sailors]]\n[[Category:1992 America's Cup sailors]]\n[[Category:1995 America's Cup sailors]]\n[[Category:2000 America's Cup sailors]]\n[[Category:2003 America's Cup sailors]]\n[[Category:2013 America's Cup sailors]]\n[[Category:World champions in sailing for the United States of America]]\n[[Category:San Francisco State University alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{use mdy dates|date=November 2013}}\n{{Infobox sailor\n| name = Paul Cayard\n| image = Paul-Cayard.jpg\n| imagesize =\n| caption = \n| fullname = Paul Pierre Cayard\n| nicknames =\n| nationality = [[United States|American]]\n| classes = [[Star (sailboat)|Star]]\n| club = \n| collegeteam = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1959|05|19|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[San Francisco]], [[California]], USA\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| height = \n| weight = \n| retired = \n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalCompetition|World Championships}}\n{{MedalGold|[[Star World Championships|1988 Buenos Aires]]|Star class}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[Star World Championships|1984 Vilamoura]]|Star class}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[Star World Championships|1985 Nassau]]|Star class}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[Star World Championships|1987 Chicago]]|Star class}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[Star World Championships|1992 San Francisco]]|Star class}}\n}}\n\n'''Paul Pierre Cayard''' (born May 19, 1959) is an American [[yacht]]sman and professional sailor.   He has competed at multiple world championship level [[sailing (sport)|sailing]] events, including the [[America's Cup]], the [[Whitbread Round the World Race]],the [[Volvo Ocean Race]] and the [[Olympic Games]]. In 1998 he was selected as the [[US Sailor of the Year Awards|US Rolex Yachtsmen of the Year]]. He has won seven world championships, twice participated in the Olympic Games and seven times in the America's Cup.   In 2002 he was elected into the Sailing World Hall of Fame.\n\n==Biography==\nPaul Cayard was born in [[San Francisco]], [[California]].  He began sailing in 1967 at the age of eight.  He graduated in 1981 with a degree in business management from [[San Francisco State University]].   He speaks three languages: [[English language|English]], [[French language|French]] and [[Italian language|Italian]].  He enjoys flying and holds a [[Pilot certification in the United States|pilots certification]] for single engine aircraft.  Of all his sailing accomplishments, he counts his 1988 Star Class world championship as his most prized victory.<ref name=Cayard>{{cite web|url=http://www.cayardsailing.com/cs_PaulCayard.cfm|title=Paul Cayard Profile|work=Cayard Sailing|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100601092853/http://www.cayardsailing.com/cs_PaulCayard.cfm|archivedate=June 1, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nCayard is a member of four different yacht clubs,  the St. Francis Yacht Club,  the San Francisco Yacht Club, the Encinal Yacht Club, and the Yacht Club de Monaco.<ref name=Cayard/>\n\nFor the 34th America's Cup in San Francisco, Paul Cayard was the CEO of [[Team Artemis|Artemis Racing]].<ref>http://www.sailingworld.com/blogs/racing/americas-cup/complexity-squared</ref>\n\n== Sailing career ==\nFrom an early age Cayard showed great promise as a sailor, and by his early teens was successfully sailing high performance dinghies such as the [[505 (dinghy)|International 505]] and Laser. As Cayard grew and became more proficient in sailing, he gained the notice of [[Tom Blackaller]], who invited Cayard to crew for him on his [[Star (sailboat)|Star class]] sailboat.  Blackaller would become an influential mentor, and the Star Class would become a lifelong passion for Cayard.\n\nIn 1984, Cayard was selected as an alternate in the [[Olympic Games]] for the USA sailing team.  Sailing in the Star Class, he won the silver medal at the pre-Olympic regatta in 2003, going on to finish 5th at the 2004 Summer Olympic Games in [[Athens]].\n\nCayard has competed in a broad range of ocean racing events with an impressive record. He has won the 1994 [[Kenwood Cup]], the 1994 and 1996 [[Sardinia Cup]], and the 1995 [[Admirals Cup]]. His top achievement in this arena was becoming the first American to win the [[Volvo Ocean Race|Whitbread Round the World]] in 1997/1998 as skipper of [[EF Language]]. He beat out ten other yachts for the prize over a course of 32,000 miles (51,500&nbsp;km).\n\nAs of 2006, Cayard competed in the Volvo Ocean Race as skipper of ''Pirates of the Caribbean'' syndicate sponsored by [[The Walt Disney Company]] in reference to the movie of the same name. Cayard Sailing, Inc. managed the syndicate.  The team won the final leg into Gothenburg and finished the overall race in 2nd place.\n\nIn 2007, Paul Cayard and Russell Coutts announced the launch of the World Sailing League in partnership with internationally renowned Portuguese sports promoter, Jo\u00e3o Lagos. The World Sailing League (WSL) will be held at premier sailing locations around the world with the series winner receiving $2 million in prize money.\n\nIn 2009, Cayard joined [[Artemis Racing]], owned by [[Torbj\u00f6rn T\u00f6rnqvist]].  Cayard was the Skipper of the Louis Vuitton Trophy team and Tactician onboard TP52 Artemis (www.artemisracing.com).  \n[[Artemis Racing]] became the Challenger of Record in the [[34th America's Cup]] in 2010 and Cayard became CEO.\n\n=== America's Cup ===\nCayard's first [[America's Cup]] was in 1983 aboard [[Tom Blackaller|Tom Blackaller's]] ''Defender'' as a jib trimmer. ''Defender'' finished third in the defender selection series. For the [[1987 America's Cup]] series, Cayard moved up to tactician and alternate helmsman on Blackaller's new boat ''USA'', which lost out to [[Dennis Conner]]'s ''Stars & Stripes'' for the right to challenge for the cup.<ref>[http://www.americaone.org/cup/history7.html History of the America\u2019s Cup - The Cup Down Under]</ref>\n\nFor the [[1992 America's Cup]], Cayard became manager and skipper of ''[[Il Moro di Venezia]]'' from Italy, a syndicate backed by [[Raul Gardini]]. In 1991, he won the first ever [[International America's Cup Class]] world championship. Over the months long challenger selection series, Cayard's team beat out seven other teams from six other countries to win the [[1992 Louis Vuitton Cup]] and gain the right to challenge for the America's Cup. Part of the challenge included protests where Cayard successfully protested the employment of a bowsprit on the [[Team New Zealand|New Zealand challenge]].\n\nThough ''Il Moro di Venezia'' was outclassed in the America's Cup races by the faster ''[[America\u00b3]]'', Cayard's expertise in sailing provided some memorable moments. In the second race of the series, his yacht won the start and maintained a small lead for the entire race. He employed classic match racing tactics throughout the race, and at the downwind finish managed to beat ''America\u00b3'' by three seconds, producing what was at the time the smallest winning margin in cup history. Cayard went on to lose this series 4-1.\n\nIn 1995, Cayard rejoined an American effort for the America's Cup, joining Team Dennis Conner aboard ''[[Stars & Stripes (yacht)|Stars & Stripes]]'' as primary helmsman. Though ''Stars & Stripes'' was noticeably slower than other boats on the defender series, the syndicate managed to win the [[1995 Citizen Cup]] for the right to defend the Cup. In an unprecedented move, Team Dennis Conner decided to use the faster yacht ''[[List of IACC yachts|Young America]]'' from the PACT 95 syndicate to defend the Cup. Cayard and this syndicate ended up losing the Cup 5-0 to [[Team New Zealand]], who had won the [[1995 Louis Vuitton Cup]].\n\nWith the change in venue and hemisphere for the Cup, the next America's Cup was not held until 2000. For the [[2000 America's Cup]], Cayard formed his own syndicate with backing from a number of sponsors and named it ''[[International America's Cup Class|AmericaOne]]''. The sponsoring yacht club was [[St. Francis Yacht Club]] of San Francisco. This syndicate competed against 14 challengers from 10 nations for the right to challenge for the Cup. ''AmericaOne'' reached the finals of the [[2000 Louis Vuitton Cup]] racing against ''Prada'' for the right to challenge against [[Team New Zealand]] for the 2000 America's Cup. The final over the best of nine races was hotly contested, with neither yacht ever winning by more than two minutes. ''Prada'' won the first race, and ''AmericaOne'' the second. ''Prada'' went on to win the next two races, putting ''AmericaOne'' at a 3-1 disadvantage. ''AmericaOne'' then proceeded to win the next three races in a row and appeared on the brink of winning the Louis Vuitton Cup. However, equipment fatigue and failure proved decisive, several spinnakers were blown out, and ''Prada'' ended up winning the next two races and the series, 5-4, earning the right to challenge for the Cup.  Prada ultimately lost in the America's Cup, 5-0 to the defender Team New Zealand.<ref>[http://www.americaone.org/cup/history8.html History of the America\u2019s Cup - Big Boats Reborn]</ref>\n\nFollowing the conclusion of the 2000 America's Cup, Cayard recommended to the ''AmericaOne'' syndicate board of trustees that the syndicate should not compete for the [[2003 America's Cup]], citing significant financial and recruiting obstacles. Assets of AmericaOne were eventually sold to [[Larry Ellison]] who founded the Oracle Racing syndicate, later joining forces with BMW Racing to form [[Oracle BMW Racing]], with Cayard as skipper. Cayard later was moved out of the skipper position into an administrative position and ultimately left the syndicate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2002/WORLD/sailing/12/11/cayard.ppl/index.html|title=Cayard Laments Oracle Move|work=CNN Inside Sailing|date=December 11, 2002}}</ref><ref>[http://www.yachtracing.com/richroberts/012903.htm Cayard: the AC From the Outside (en)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929201533/http://www.yachtracing.com/richroberts/012903.htm |date=September 29, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2007, Cayard was involved in the [[2007 America's Cup]] as Technical Advisor to Desafio Espanol 2007. Cayard also commentated on the [[2007 Louis Vuitton Cup]] and on the [[2007 America's Cup]] for [[La7]], the Italian broadcast rights holder.  On 12 October 2007, Cayard announced that he was joining [[Desafio Espanol]] as Sports Director for the 33rd America's Cup.\n\nFor the 33rd America's Cup, Cayard provided commentary for Eurosport and in 2009 joined Torbjorn Tornqvist's sailing on Artemis Racing for the TP52 and Louis Vuitton Trophy regattas. Cayard also helmed RC44 Katusha on the RC44 Championship Tour from 2010-2012.\n\n=== Achievements ===\n{{updated|27 September 2015|<ref>https://members.sailing.org/sailors/biog.php?memberid=40455</ref>}}\n{| {{AchievementTable|Event=yes|NotesOff=y}}\n|-\n| 1978 || [[Star World Championships]] || [[San Francisco]], USA || 4th || Star class\n|-\n| 1979 || [[Star World Championships]] || [[Marstrand]], Sweden || 17th || Star class\n|-\n| 1984 || [[Star World Championships]] || [[Vilamoura]], Portugal || style=\"background:#c96;\"| 3rd || Star class\n|-\n| 1985 || [[Star World Championships]] || [[Nassau, Bahamas|Nassau]], Bahamas || style=\"background:#c96;\"| 3rd || Star class\n|-\n| 1987 || [[Star World Championships]] || [[Chicago]], USA || style=\"background:#c96;\"| 3rd || Star class\n|-\n| 1988 || [[Star World Championships]] || [[Buenos Aires]], Argentina ||style=\"background:gold;\"| 1st || Star class\n|-\n| 1989 || [[Star World Championships]] || [[Porto Cervo]], Italy || 10th || Star class\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 1991 || [[IACC World Championship]]  || [[San Diego]], ||1st|| America's Cup\n|-\n| [[IOR 50 World Championship]] || [[Japan]], ||1st|| Intl. 50' Class\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 1992 || [[ISAF Open Match Racing World Championship|IYRU Match Racing World Championships]] || [[Long Beach, California|Long Beach]], USA || 5th || Match racing\n|-\n| [[Star World Championships]] || [[San Francisco]], USA || style=\"background:#c96;\"| 3rd || Star class\n|-\n| 1996 || [[Star World Championships]] || [[Rio de Janeiro]], Brazil || 4th || Star class\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 2002 || [[Star World Championships]] || [[Marina del Rey]], USA || 4th || Star class\n|-\n| [[Farr 40 World Championships]] || [[Paradise Island]], Bahamas || 6th || Farr 40 class\n|-\n| 2003 || [[ISAF Sailing World Championships]] || [[Cadiz]], Spain || 8th || Star class\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 2004 || [[Star World Championships]] || [[Gaeta]], Italy || 5th || Star class\n|-\n| Olympic Games || [[Athens]], Greece || 5th || Star class\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 2008 || [[Farr 40 World Championships]] || [[Florida]], USA || 11th || Farr 40 class\n|-\n| [[TP52 World Championships]] || [[Lanzarote]], Spain || 7th || TP52 class\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 2009 || [[505 World Championships]] || [[San Francisco]], USA || 7th || 505 class\n|-\n| [[TP52 World Championships]] || [[Palma, Majorca|Palma]], Spain || style=\"background:#c96;\"| 3rd || TP52 class\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 2010 || [[RC44 World Championships]] || [[Puerto Calero]], Spain || 4th || RC44 class\n|-\n| [[TP52 World Championships]] || [[Valencia]], Spain || 4th || TP52 class\n|}\n\n* Won the El Toro class North American championship in the under 18 category in 1975.\n* Won the Star class world championship in 1988.\n* Won the [[Maxi yacht|Maxi class]] world championship in 1988 aboard ''Il Moro di Venezia III''.\n* Won the 1989 One Ton class world championship.\n* Won the 1991 50-foot world championship aboard ''Abracadabra'' in Japan.\n* 1991 Yachting magazine Yachtsman of the Year.\n* Won the Louis Vuitton Cup in 1992.\n* 1992 [[Rothmans]] Yachtsman of the Year.\n* Won the Citizens Cup in 1995 for the right to defend the America's Cup.\n* Won 1994 and 1996 Sardinia Cup (ocean racing)\n* Won 1994 Kenwood Cup (ocean racing)\n* Won the 1995 Admiral's Cup (ocean racing)\n* Won the 1996 International Level Class 40 world championship.\n* Won the 1999 Steinlager Cup.\n* Won the 1997/98 Whitbread Round the World Race (now known as the [[Volvo Ocean Race]]) as skipper of the [[Sweden|Swedish]] entry EF Language.\n* 1998 [[Rolex]] Yachtsman of the Year.\n* Won 2002 IMS world championship in [[Capri]], Italy.\n* 2002 inductee into the Sailing World Hall of Fame.\n* 2005-2006 Skippered 'Pirates of the Caribbean' in the Volvo Ocean Race, placing 2nd overall.\n* Tactician on board John Kilroy's ''Samba Pa Ti'', winner of the [[Farr 40]] North American Championships 2004, US National Championships 2004, Pacific Coast Championships 2004, and West Coast Season Championships 2004.\n* 2010 Became CEO of Artemis Racing, Challenger of Record for the 34th America's Cup, which is backed by Torbj\u00f6rn Tornqvist. \n* 2011 Inducted into the [[National Sailing Hall of Fame]] in San Diego, CA.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nshof.org/hall-of-fame/class-of-2011-extended/78-the-national-sailing-hall-of-fame/hall-of-fame-2011/333-cayard-paul-2011-hall-of-fame|title=Paul Cayard 2011 Inductee |publisher=Nshof.org |date= |accessdate=November 22, 2019}}</ref>\n* 2012 Sailed as tactician in October ACWS event in San Francisco for Artemis Racing Red.\n* 2014 Won Miami Star Winter Series - Star Mid-Winter Championship, Miami, FL.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Italy at the America's Cup]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n* [http://www.americaone.org/syndicate/cayard.html Record of world championships won]\n* [http://www.americaone.org/results-finals.html 2000 Louis Vuitton Cup finals results]\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.cayardsailing.com/ Cayard Sailing website]\n* [http://www.americascup.com/en/acclopaedia/circlinggalaxy/profil.php?idIndex=&idContent=4497  32nd America's Cup website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070227084316/http://www.wsl2009.com/  World Sailing League website]\n* [http://www.blackpearlracing.com Pirates of the Caribbean entry in the Volvo Ocean Race 2005-2006 website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070504045056/http://www.la7.it/vela/index.asp LA7 Italy's website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070629032853/http://www.la7.it/vela/video.asp Cayard's italian video]\n* [http://www.americaone.org ''AmericaOne'' website]\n* {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110603233740/https://sports.yahoo.com/olympics/torino2006/usa/paul+cayard/1726317/ |date=3 June 2011 |title=Yahoo! Sports profile for the 2006 Winter Olympics }}\n* {{ISAF|id=USAPC5}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120331213628/http://32nd.americascup.com/en/acclopaedia/boatdestiny/index.php?idIndex=0&idContent=3542 History of ''Il Moro di Venezia'' at the 1992 America's Cup]\n* [http://www.usoc.org/26_21701.htm Paul Cayard's U.S. Olympic Team bio]\n\n{{Footer World Champions Star}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cayard, Paul}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:American male sailors (sport)]