g collection of doctor's offices and medical practices is concentrated in the vicinity of [[UCONN Health Center]].\n\nFarmington is unique in that more people work within the town lines than actually live there, a characteristic atypical of a traditional suburb.\n\n==Arts and culture==\n===Locations listed on the National Register of Historic Places===\n{{unreferenced section|date=May 2018}}\n[[File:1stChurchofChrist FarmingtonCT.jpg|thumb|right|upright|First Church of Christ. Photo by [[Jack Boucher]].]]\n* [[Austin F. Williams Carriagehouse and House]] &mdash; 127 Main Street (added 1998)\n* [[Farmington Historic District (Connecticut)|Farmington Historic District]] &mdash; Porter and Mountain Rds., Main and Garden Sts., Hatter's and Hillstead Lanes, and Farmington Ave. (added 1972)\n* [[First Church of Christ, Congregational (Farmington, Connecticut)|First Church of Christ]] &mdash; 75 Main St. (added 1975)\n* [[Gen. George Cowles House]] &mdash; 130 Main St. (added 1982)\n* [[Gridley-Parsons-Staples Homestead]] &mdash; 1554 Farmington Ave. (added 1981)\n* [[Hill-Stead Museum]] (added 1991).  The estate, completed in 1901 and designed for [[Alfred Atmore Pope]] by his daughter [[Theodate Pope Riddle]], one of the first woman American architects, is known for its [[Colonial Revival architecture]].  Now a museum, its 19 rooms hold a nationally recognized collection of [[Impressionism|Impressionist]] paintings by such masters as [[\u00c9douard Manet|Manet]], [[Claude Monet|Monet]], [[James Abbott McNeill Whistler|Whistler]], [[Edgar Degas|Degas]] and [[Mary Cassatt|Cassatt]].  It is the site of the annual Sunken Garden Poetry Festival and is a [[National Historic Landmark]].\n* [[Pequabuck Bridge]] &mdash; Meadow Rd. at Pequabuck River (added 1984)\n* [[Shade Swamp Shelter]] &mdash; US 6 E of New Britain Ave. (added 1986)\n* [[Stanley-Whitman House]] &mdash; 37 High St. (added November 15, 1966)\n* [[West End Library]] &mdash; 15 School St., Unionville (added 2000)\n\n==Education==\n[[Farmington Public Schools (Connecticut)|Farmington Public Schools]] operates public schools.\n\nStudents in Farmington have access to public schools that consistently rank among the best{{which|date=January 2017}} in the nation.  The town has seven main public schools. The four K-4 elementary schools are Union School, West District School, Noah Wallace School, and East Farms School.  The recently built West Woods Upper Elementary School houses all of grades 5-6. Irving A. Robbins Middle School houses grades 7-8. [[Farmington High School (Connecticut)|Farmington High School]] serves grades 9-12 for the entire town.  In 2005, Farmington High School was ranked 125 on ''Newsweek'' Magazine's list of the best schools in the United States,<ref>{{cite news |first=Halley |last=Bondy |authorlink= |author2=Brillman, Dan |author3=Kaufman, Becca |title=The Top of the Class |url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/18757087/?sort=Rank&count=1043&Search=&start=100&limit=100&year=2005& |work=[[Newsweek]] |publisher=[[MSNBC]] |accessdate=2007-06-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070625170828/http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/18757087/?sort=Rank&count=1043&Search=&start=100&limit=100&year=2005& <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2007-06-25}}</ref> in 2006 Farmington was ranked 269<ref>{{cite news |first=Halley |last=Bondy |authorlink= |author2=Brillman, Dan |author3=Kaufman, Becca |title=The Top of the Class |url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/18757087/?sort=Rank&count=1236&Search=&start=200&limit=100&year=2006& |work=[[Newsweek]] |publisher=[[MSNBC]] |accessdate=2007-06-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071203123020/http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/18757087/?sort=Rank&count=1236&Search=&start=200&limit=100&year=2006& <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2007-12-03}}</ref> and in 2007, 298.<ref>{{cite news |first=Halley |last=Bondy |authorlink= |author2=Brillman, Dan |author3=Kaufman, Becca |title=The Top of the Class |url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/18757087/?sort=Rank&count=1327&Search=&start=200&limit=100&year=2007& |work=[[Newsweek]] |publisher=[[MSNBC]] |accessdate=2007-06-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070608095734/http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/18757087/?sort=Rank&count=1327&Search=&start=200&limit=100&year=2007& <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2007-06-08}}</ref>\n\n[[Miss Porter's School]], an exclusive [[college preparatory school]] for girls, is in Farmington. The school, whose buildings occupy much of the village center, is a significant historic and cultural institution in its own right. Founded in 1843 by educational reformer [[Sarah Porter]], Miss Porter's has long been one of the most selective preparatory schools for girls in the country.  Famous alumni include [[Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis]], [[Lilly Pulitzer]] and members of the [[Bush family|Bush]], [[Vanderbilt family|Vanderbilt]], and [[Rockefeller family|Rockefeller]] families.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n\n[[Tunxis Community College]] is in the southwest part of the town.\n\n==Infrastructure==\n[[File:UConn Health Center.jpg|thumb|UConn Health Center]]\nThe [[University of Connecticut Health Center]] in Farmington employs over 5,000 people.{{Citation needed|date=May 2009}}  The Health Center also houses John Dempsey Hospital.  The hospital provides the only full-service emergency department in the Farmington Valley and a Level III [[Neonatal Intensive Care Unit]] (NICU), one of only two in Connecticut.\n\nConnecticut's first [[Hartford Connecticut Temple|temple]] of [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] opened in Farmington in 2016.\n\n===Transportation===\n[[Connecticut Transit Hartford]] provides local bus service.\n\n==Notable people==\n<!--consensus reached to standardize this heading per WP:WikiProject Cities/US Guideline -->\n<!-- NOTICE * * * NOTICE * * * NOTICE * * * * * * * * * * * *NOTICE * * * NOTICE * * * NOTICE\u2022 Only people who already have a Wikipedia article may appear here. This establishes notability.\n\u2022 The article must mention how they are associated with the community, whether born, raised, or residing.\n\u2022 The fact of their association should have a reliable source cited.\n\u2022 Alphabetical by last name please\n\u2022 All others will be deleted without further explanation\nEND OF NOTICE * * * * * * * * * * * * END OF NOTICE * * * * * * * * * * * *END OF NOTICE -->\n*[[Tim Abromaitis]], professional basketball player for [[Zenit Saint Petersburg]]\n* [[Steve Addazio]], Boston College head football coach<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bceagles.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/steve_addazio_833257.html |title=Steve Addazio |publisher=Official Site of The Boston College Eagles |access-date=March 7, 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131218104501/http://www.bceagles.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/steve_addazio_833257.html |archive-date=December 18, 2013 |df= }}</ref>\n*[[Richard M. Bissell Jr.]], [[Central Intelligence Agency]] officer responsible for the [[Lockheed U-2|U-2 spy plane]] project and the [[Bay of Pigs Invasion]]<ref name=\"Binder\">{{cite news |last=Binder |first=David |date=February 8, 1994 |title=Richard M. Bissell, 84, Is Dead; Helped Plan Bay of Pigs Invasion |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9803EED81638F93BA35751C0A962958260 |newspaper=The New York Times |location=New York |accessdate=January 2, 2015}}</ref>\n*[[Nick Bonino]], NHL hockey player<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.anaheimcalling.com/2009/10/19/1091964/put-down-the-cigarette-and-drop|title= Put Down The Cigarette . . . And Drop Out of BU.|publisher =SB Nation|accessdate= March 7, 2014}}</ref>\n*[[Anna Roosevelt Cowles]], eldest sister of President [[Theodore Roosevelt]] and aunt of [[Eleanor Roosevelt]]<ref>{{cite web|url=  http://articles.courant.com/2013-05-31/features/hc-farmington-cowles-garden-0531-20130531_1_green-garden-farmington-tour-farmington-library|title='Green' Garden with Roosevelt Ties Part of Farmington Tour|publisher =The Courant|accessdate= March 7, 2014}}</ref>\n*[[Ron Francis]], NHL hockey player, former Farmington resident\n*[[Kevin Galvin]], business and health care advocate<ref>{{cite web|url=  http://articles.courant.com/1996-11-21/business/9611210020_1_home-depot-home-repairs-booming-business|title= Handyman at Work on a Booming Business|publisher =The Courant|accessdate= March 7, 2014}}</ref>\n*[[Michael Gladis]], actor, raised in Farmington and graduated from [[Farmington High School (Connecticut)|Farmington High School]]<ref>{{cite web|url=  http://www.courant.com/community/farmington/hc-famous-folks-with-a-farmington-connection-2-002,0,5952091.photo|title= Michael Gladis|publisher =The Courant|accessdate= March 7, 2014}}</ref>\n*[[George Gleason (politician)|George Gleason]], Wisconsin state assemblyman<ref>{{cite book|title=THE LEGISLATIVE MANUAL OF THE STATE OF WISCONSIN|edition=15th|location=Madison, Wis.|year=1876|page=475}}</ref>\n*[[Orville Hungerford]], U.S. congressman<ref>{{cite dictionary|url=  http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=H000968|title= HUNGERFORD, Orville, (1790 - 1851) |dictionary =Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate= March 7, 2014}}</ref>\n*[[Curtis Jackson]], hip hop rapper and entrepreneur, more commonly known as [[50 Cent]]<ref>{{cite web|url=  http://www.courant.com/business/real-estate/hc-50-cents-farmington-mansion-still-on-the-market-20120815,0,4756891.photogallery|title= 50 Cent's Farmington Mansion Still On The Market|publisher =The Courant|accessdate= March 6, 2014}}</ref>\n*[[Tebucky Jones]], former [[New England Patriots]] football player{{Citation needed|date = March 2014}}<!--MISSING CONNECTION TO FARMINGTON-->\n*[[Chauncey Langdon]], U.S. congressman from [[Vermont]], born in Farmington<ref>{{cite dictionary|url=  http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=L000066|title= LANGDON, Chauncey, (1763 - 1830)|dictionary =Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate= March 7, 2014}}</ref>\n*[[Timothy Merrill]], [[Secretary of State of Vermont]]<ref>{{cite book |last=Thompson |first=Daniel. P. |date=1860 |title=History of the Town of Montpelier |url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_XjrM-mA4Uo8C |location=Montpelier, VT |publisher=E. P. Walton |pages=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_XjrM-mA4Uo8C/page/n214 211]\u2013213}}</ref>\n*[[Erin Pac]], U.S. Olympic Women's [[bobsled]] team and [[Bobsleigh at the 2010 Winter Olympics \u2013 Two-woman|two-woman bobsled event]] bronze medalist at the 2010 Winter Olympics<ref>{{cite web|url=  http://articles.courant.com/2010-03-13/sports/hc-erin-pac-0313.artmar13_1_heptathlete-at-springfield-college-erin-pac-elana-meyers|title= Erin Pac Returns Home With Olympic Medal|publisher =The Courant|accessdate= March 7, 2014}}</ref>\n*[[Alfred Atmore Pope]], industrialist and art collector, resided at [[Hill-Stead]] from 1901 to 1913; father of Theodate Pope Riddle<ref>{{cite book|last=Linebaugh|first=Donald|title=The Springfield Gas Machine: Illuminating Industry and Leisure, 1860s\u20131920s|year=2012|publisher=Univ. of Tennessee Press|page=302|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uHVQVJknYnMC&pg=PA302&lpg=PA302&dq=Alfred+Atmore+Pope+Farmington+ct&source=bl&ots=n6TSwHNkpG&sig=WenXl7pQUop_flwKA_lkyR6SS3Y&hl=en&sa=X&ei=HhUaU6i4PIPt2QWKn4F4&ved=0CGsQ6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=Alfred%20Atmore%20Pope%20Farmington%20ct&f=false}}</ref> \n*[[Theodate Pope Riddle]], noted architect and founder of [[Hill\u2013Stead Museum]]<ref>{{cite book|last=[[Joan Marter]]|first=|title=The Grove Encyclopedia of American Art, Volume 1|year=2011|publisher=Oxford University Press|page=147|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sPGdBxzaWj0C&pg=RA3-PA147&lpg=RA3-PA147&dq=Alfred+Atmore+Pope+Farmington+ct&source=bl&ots=qalgFCCFyi&sig=8DmkdbgYHgv0pVn5PDi8-AR-zpE&hl=en&sa=X&ei=HhUaU6i4PIPt2QWKn4F4&ved=0CFgQ6AEwBQ#v=onepage&q=Alfred%20Atmore%20Pope%20Farmington%20ct&f=false}}</ref> \n*[[Aric Rindfleisch]], professor of [[business administration]] and department head at the College of Business at Illinois<ref>https://business.illinois.edu/profile/aric-rindfleisch/</ref>\n*[[Kathleen Rubins]], NASA astronaut and 60th woman in space; born in Farmington<ref>https://www.jsc.nasa.gov/Bios/htmlbios/rubins-k.pdf</ref>\n*[[Pawel Szajda]], actor, born and raised in Farmington, graduated from [[Farmington High School (Connecticut)|Farmington High School]]<ref>{{cite web|url=  http://www.courant.com/community/farmington/hc-pawel-szajda-20130123,0,4524402.photo|title= Pawel Szajda|publisher =The Courant|accessdate= March 7, 2014}}</ref>\n*[[Kristen Taekman]], model and cast member of ''[[The Real Housewives of New York City]]'', born and raised in Farmington\n*[[Eli Todd]], pioneer in the [[Treatment of mental disorders|treatment of mental disorders]])\n*[[John Treadwell]], fourth governor of the state of Connecticut<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nga.org/cms/home/governors/past-governors-bios/page_connecticut/col2-content/main-content-list/title_treadwell_john.html |title=Connecticut Governor John Treadwell |publisher=National Governors Association |accessdate=May 24, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Mike Tyson]], former resident. In 2004, 50 Cent bought Tyson's {{convert|18|acre|m2|adj=on}} compound, which is located about {{convert|2|mi|km}} southeast from the town center.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2007/11/29/entertainment/main3551840.shtml | work=CBS News | title=50 Cent Shows Off Mansion On 'Cribs' | date=2007-11-29}}</ref>\n*[[Suzy Whaley]], the first female golfer to qualify for a PGA event; currently the president of the LPGA<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.pga.com/professionals/suzy-m-whaley-pga|title= Suzy M. Whaley, PGA|publisher =PGA|accessdate= March 7, 2014}}</ref>\n*[[Wilford Woodruff]], fourth [[President of the Church (LDS Church)|president]] of [[the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] (LDS Church),  born in Farmington<ref>{{cite web|url=  https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/study/manual/presidents-of-the-church-teacher-manual-religion-345/wilford-woodruff-fourth-president-of-the-church?lang=eng|title= Wilford Woodruff-Fourth President of the Church|publisher =The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-Day Saints|accessdate= March 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\n\n{{Portal|Connecticut}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://www.farmington-ct.org/ Town of Farmington official website]\n*[http://www.farmingtonchamber.com/ Farmington Chamber of Commerce]\n\n{{Connecticut}}\n{{Hartford County, Connecticut}}\n{{Greater Hartford}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Farmington, Connecticut| ]]\n[[Category:Towns in Hartford County, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Populated places on the Underground Railroad]]\n[[Category:Towns in Connecticut]]\n[[Category:1645 establishments in Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Greater Hartford]]\n", "name_user": "Jamesmcmahon0", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: 5-6 \u2192 5\u20136 (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Farmington,_Connecticut"}
{"title_page": "Vietnamese phonology", "text_new": "{{selfref|For assistance with IPA transcriptions of Vietnamese for Wikipedia articles, see [[Help:IPA/Vietnamese]].}}\n{{IPA notice}}\nThis article is a technical description of the sound system of the [[Vietnamese language]], including [[phonetics]] and [[phonology]]. Two main varieties of Vietnamese, [[Hanoi]] and [[Ho Chi Minh City]] (Saigon), are described below.\n\n==Initial consonants==\nInitial consonants which exist only in the Hanoi dialect are in red, while those that exist only in the Saigon dialect are in blue.\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|- style=\"font-size: 90%;\"\n! colspan=\"2\" width=25% |\n! width=10% | [[Labial consonant|Labial]]\n! width=10% | [[Dental consonant|Dental]]/<br>[[Alveolar consonant|Alveolar]]\n! width=10% | [[Postalveolar consonant|Retroflex]]\n! width=10% | [[Palatal consonant|Palatal]]\n! width=10% | [[Velar consonant|Velar]]\n! width=10% | [[Glottal consonant|Glottal]]\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | [[Nasal consonant|Nasal]]\n| {{IPA link|m}}\n| {{IPA link|n}}\n|\n| {{IPA link|\u0272}}\n| {{IPA link|\u014b}}\n|\n|-\n! rowspan=\"3\" | [[Stop consonant|Stop]]/<br>[[Affricate consonant|Affricate]]\n! <small>[[Tenuis consonant|tenuis]]</small>\n| ({{IPA link|p}})\n| {{IPA link|t}}\n| style=\"background-color: #ccf\" | {{IPA link|\u0288}}\n| {{IPA link|c}}\n| {{IPA link|k}}\n| ({{IPA link|\u0294}})\n|-\n! <small>[[Aspirated consonant|aspirated]]</small>\n|\n| {{IPA|t\u02b0}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! <small>[[Glottalization|glottalized]]</small>\n| {{IPA link|\u0253}}\n| {{IPA link|\u0257}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | [[Fricative consonant|Fricative]]\n! <small>[[Voicelessness|voiceless]]</small>\n| {{IPA link|f}}\n| {{IPA link|s}}\n| style=\"background-color: #ccf\" | {{IPA link|\u0282}}\n|\n| {{IPA link|x}}\n| {{IPA link|h}}\n|-\n! <small>[[Voice (phonetics)|voiced]]</small>\n| style=\"background-color: #fcc\" | {{IPA link|v}}\n| {{IPA link|z}}~{{IPA link|j}}\n|\n|\n| {{IPA link|\u0263}}\n|\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | [[Approximant consonant|Approximant]]\n|\n| {{IPA link|l}}\n|\n|\n| {{IPA link|w}}\n|\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | [[Rhotic consonant|Rhotic]]\n|\n| style=\"background-color: #ccf\" | {{IPA|r}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|}\n* /w/ is the only initial consonant permitted to form [[consonant cluster]]s with other consonants.\n* {{IPA|/p/}} occurs syllable-initially only in [[loan word]]s, and is mostly converted into {{IPA|/\u0253/}} (as in ''s\u00e2m banh'', derived from French ''champagne'').\n* The glottalized stops are preglottalized and voiced:  {{IPA|[\u0294\u0253, \u0294\u0257]}} (the [[glottis]] is always closed before the oral closure). This glottal closure is often not released before the release of the oral closure, resulting in the characteristic [[implosive]] pronunciation. However, sometimes the glottal closure is released prior to the oral release in which case the stops are pronounced {{IPA|[\u0294b, \u0294d]}}. Therefore, the primary characteristic is preglottalization with implosion being secondary.\n* {{IPA|/\u0253, m/}} are [[Bilabial consonant|bilabial]], while {{IPA|/f, v/}} are [[Labiodental consonant|labiodental]].\n* {{IPA|/t, t\u02b0/}} are [[Denti-alveolar consonant|denti-alveolar]] ({{IPA|[t\u032a, t\u032a\u02b0]}}), while {{IPA|/\u0257, n, l/}} are [[Apical consonant|apico]]-[[alveolar consonant|alveolar]].<ref name=\"Kirby 382\">{{Harvcoltxt|Kirby|2011|p=382}}</ref>\n* {{IPA|/c, \u0272/}} are phonetically [[Laminal consonant|lamino]]-[[palatoalveolar]]  (the blade of the tongue makes contact behind the [[alveolar ridge]]).\n* {{IPA|/\u0288, c/}} are often slightly [[affricate]]d {{IPA|[\u0288\u0361\u0282, t\u0361\u0255]}}, but they are [[Aspiration (phonetics)|unaspirated]].\n* A [[glottal stop]] {{IPA|[\u0294]}} is inserted before words that begin with a vowel or {{IPA|/w/}}:\n\n:{| cellpadding=\"5\" style=\"line-height: 1.0em;\"\n| ''\u0103n''\n| 'to eat'\n| {{IPA|/\u0103n/}}\n| \u2192\n| {{IPA|[\u0294\u0103n]}}\n|-\n| ''u\u1ef7''\n| 'to delegate'\n| {{IPA|/wi/}}\n| \u2192\n| {{IPA|[\u0294wi]}}\n|}\n\n===Hanoi initials===\n* ''d'', ''gi'' and ''r'' are all pronounced {{IPA|/z/}}.\n* ''ch'' and ''tr'' are both pronounced {{IPA|/c/}}, while ''x'' and ''s'' are both pronounced {{IPA|/s/}}.\n* Some rural speakers merge {{IPA|/l/}} and {{IPA|/n/}} into {{IPA|/l/}}, although this is not considered standard.<ref name=\"Kirby 382\"/>\n\n===Saigon initials===\n* ''d'' and ''gi'' are both pronounced {{IPA|/j/}}.\n* Historically, {{IPA|/v/}} is pronounced {{IPA|[j]}} in common speech, merging with ''d'' and ''gi''. However, it is becoming distinct and pronounced as {{IPA|[v]}}, especially in careful speech. In traditional performance including C\u1ea3i l\u01b0\u01a1ng, \u0110\u1eddn ca t\u00e0i t\u1eed, H\u00e1t b\u1ed9i and some old speakers of Overseas Vietnamese, it is pronounced as consonant cluster [bj], [\u03b2j] or [vj].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Thompson|first=Laurence C.|date=1959-07|title=Saigon Phonemics|url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/411232?origin=crossref|journal=Language|volume=35|issue=3|pages=454|doi=10.2307/411232}}</ref>\n* Historically, a distinction is made between ''ch'' {{IPA|/c/}} and ''tr'' {{IPA|/\u0288/}}, as well as between ''x'' {{IPA|/s/}} and ''s'' {{IPA|/\u0282/}}. However, these two pairs are becoming merged as {{IPA|/c/}} and {{IPA|/s/}} respectively.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Ph\u1ea1m|2008|p=35}}</ref>\n* In southern speech, the phoneme {{IPA|/r/}}, generally represented in Vietnamese linguistics by the letter {{angbr|r}}, has a number of variant pronunciations that depend on the speaker. More than one pronunciation may even be found within a single speaker. It may occur as a [[Voiced retroflex fricative|retroflex fricative]] {{IPA|[\u0290]}}, an [[alveolar approximant]] {{IPA|[\u0279]}}, a [[Alveolar tap|flap]] {{IPA|[\u027e]}} or a [[Alveolar trill|trill]] {{IPA|[r]}}.\n* Some rural speakers from Mekong Delta merge {{IPA|/r/}} and {{IPA|/\u0263/}} into {{IPA|/\u0263/}}, or {{IPA|/r/}} and /j/ into /j/, although this is not considered standard.\n\n===Comparison of initials===\nThe table below summarizes these sound correspondences:\n\n:{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" | [[Diaphoneme]]\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Hanoi\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Saigon\n! colspan=\"3\" | Example\n|-\n! word\n! Hanoi\n! Saigon\n|-\n! {{IPA|/v/}}\n| {{IPA|/v/}}\n| {{IPA|/v/}} or {{IPA|/j/}}\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" | ''v\u1ee3'' &nbsp; 'wife'\n| {{IPA|[v\u0259\u02e8\u02e9\u02c0]}}\n| {{IPA|[v\u0259\u02e8\u02e7]}} or {{IPA|[j\u0259\u02e8\u02e7]}}\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|/z/}}\n| rowspan=\"3\" | {{IPA|/z/}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|/j/}}\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" | ''da'' &nbsp; 'skin'\n| rowspan=\"3\" | {{IPA|[za\u02e7]}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|[ja\u02e7]}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" | ''gia'' &nbsp; 'to add'\n|-\n! {{IPA|/r/}}\n| {{IPA|/r/}}\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" | ''ra'' &nbsp; 'to go out'\n| {{IPA|[ra\u02e7]}}\n|-\n! {{IPA|/c/}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|/c/}}\n| {{IPA|/c/}}\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" | ''ch\u1ebb'' &nbsp; 'split'\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|[c\u025b\u02e7\u02e9]}}\n| {{IPA|[c\u025b\u02e9\u02e5]}}\n|-\n! {{IPA|/\u0288/}}\n| {{IPA|/c/}} or {{IPA|/\u0288/}}\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" | ''tr\u1ebb'' &nbsp; 'young'\n| {{IPA|[c\u025b\u02e9\u02e5]}} or {{IPA|[\u0288\u025b\u02e9\u02e5]}}\n|-\n! {{IPA|/s/}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|/s/}}\n| {{IPA|/s/}}\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" | ''xinh'' &nbsp; 'beautiful'\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|[si\u014b\u031f\u02e7]}}\n| {{IPA|[s\u0268n\u02e7]}}\n|-\n! {{IPA|/\u0282/}}\n| {{IPA|/s/}} or {{IPA|/\u0282/}}\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" | ''sinh'' &nbsp; 'born'\n| {{IPA|[s\u0268n\u02e7]}} or {{IPA|[\u0282\u0268n\u02e7]}}\n|}\n\n==Vowels==\n\n===Vowel nuclei===\n[[File:Hanoi Vietnamese vowel chart.svg|thumb|upright=1.13|Vowel chart of Hanoi [[monophthong]]s according to {{Harvcoltxt|Kirby|2011|p=384}}]]\n[[File:Hanoi Vietnamese diphthong chart.svg|thumb|upright=1.13|Vowel chart of Hanoi [[diphthong]]s according to {{Harvcoltxt|Kirby|2011|p=384}}]]\n\n:{| class=\"wikitable nowrap\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!  \n! [[Front vowel|Front]]\n! [[Central vowel|Central]]\n! [[Back vowel|Back]]\n|- style=\"height: 65px\"\n! [[Centering diphthong|Centering]]\n| {{IPA|/i\u0259\u032f/}} {{angbr|ia~i\u00ea}}\n| {{IPA|/\u0268\u0259\u032f/}} {{angbr|\u01b0a~\u01b0\u01a1}}\n| {{IPA|/u\u0259\u032f/}} {{angbr|ua~u\u00f4}}\n|- style=\"height: 65px\"\n! [[Close vowel|Close]]\n| {{IPAslink|i}} {{angbr|i, y}}\n| {{IPAslink|\u0268}} {{angbr|\u01b0}}\n| {{IPAslink|u}} {{angbr|u}}\n|- style=\"height: 65px;\"\n! [[Close-mid vowel|Close-mid]]/<br>[[Mid vowel|Mid]]\n| {{IPAslink|e}} {{angbr|\u00ea}}\n| {{IPAslink|\u0259}} {{angbr|\u01a1}}\n<br>{{IPAslink|\u0259|\u0259\u0306}} {{angbr|\u00e2}}\n| {{IPAslink|o}} {{angbr|\u00f4}}\n|- style=\"height: 65px;\"\n! [[Open-mid vowel|Open-mid]]/<br>[[Open vowel|Open]]\n| {{IPAslink|\u025b}} {{angbr|e}}\n| {{IPAslink|\u00e4|a}} {{angbr|a}}\n<br>{{IPAslink|\u00e4|\u0103}} {{angbr|\u0103}}\n| {{IPAslink|\u0254}} {{angbr|o}}\n|}\n\nThe [[International Phonetic Alphabet|IPA]] chart of vowel nuclei above is based on the sounds in Hanoi Vietnamese; other regions may have different inventories. Vowel nuclei consist of [[monophthong]]s (simple [[vowel]]s) and three [[centering diphthong]]s.\n\n* All vowels are [[Roundedness|unrounded]] except for the four back rounded vowels: {{IPA|/u, o, \u0254, u\u0259\u032f/}}.\n* {{IPA|/\u0259\u0306/}} and {{IPA|/\u0103/}} are pronounced [[Vowel length|short]] \u2014 shorter than the other vowels.\n* While there are small consistent spectral differences between {{IPA|/\u0259\u0306/}} and {{IPA|/\u0259/}}, it has not been established that they are perceptually significant.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Kirby|2011|p=384}}</ref>\n* {{IPA|/\u0268/}}: Many descriptions, such as Thompson,<ref name=\"Harvcoltxt|Thompson|1965\"/> {{Harvcoltxt|Nguy\u1ec5n|1970}}, {{Harvcoltxt|Nguy\u1ec5n|1997}}, consider this vowel to be [[Close back unrounded vowel|close back unrounded]]: {{IPA|[\u026f]}}. However, Han's<ref name=\"Harvcoltxt|Han|1966\">{{Harvcoltxt|Han|1966}}</ref> instrumental analysis indicates that it is more central than back. {{Harvcoltxt|Hoang|1965}}, {{Harvcoltxt|Brunelle|2003}} and {{Harvcoltxt|Ph\u1ea1m|2006}} also transcribe this vowel as central.\n{{clear}}\n\n===Closing sequences===\nIn Vietnamese, vowel nuclei are able to combine with offglides {{IPA|/j/}} or {{IPA|/w/}} to form closing [[diphthong]]s and [[triphthong]]s. Below is a chart<ref>From {{Harvcoltxt|Nguy\u1ec5n|1997}}</ref> listing the closing sequences of general northern speech.\n\n:{| class=\"wikitable nowrap\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|/w/}} offglide\n! colspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|/j/}} offglide\n|-\n! [[Front vowel|Front]]\n! colspan=\"2\" | [[Central vowel|Central]]\n! [[Back vowel|Back]]\n|-\n! [[Centering diphthong|Centering]]\n| {{IPA|/i\u0259\u032fw/}} {{angbr|i\u00eau}}\n| {{IPA|/\u0268\u0259\u032fw/}} {{angbr|\u01b0\u01a1u}}\n| {{IPA|/\u0268\u0259\u032fj/}} {{angbr|\u01b0\u01a1i}}\n| {{IPA|/u\u0259\u032fj/}} {{angbr|u\u00f4i}}\n|-\n! [[Close vowel|Close]]\n| {{IPA|/iw/}} {{angbr|iu}}\n| {{IPA|/\u0268w/}} {{angbr|\u01b0u}}\n| {{IPA|/\u0268j/}} {{angbr|\u01b0i}}\n| {{IPA|/uj/}} {{angbr|ui}}\n|-\n! [[Close-mid vowel|Close-mid]]/<br>[[Mid vowel|Mid]]\n| {{IPA|/ew/}} {{angbr|\u00eau}}\n| \u2013\n<br>{{IPA|/\u0259\u0306w/}} {{angbr|\u00e2u}}\n| {{IPA|/\u0259j/}} {{angbr|\u01a1i}}\n<br>{{IPA|/\u0259\u0306j/}} {{angbr|\u00e2y}}\n| {{IPA|/oj/}} {{angbr|\u00f4i}}\n|-\n! [[Open-mid vowel|Open-mid]]/<br>[[Open vowel|Open]]\n| {{IPA|/\u025bw/}} {{angbr|eo}}\n| {{IPA|/aw/}} {{angbr|ao}}\n<br>{{IPA|/\u0103w/}} {{angbr|au}}\n| {{IPA|/aj/}} {{angbr|ai}}\n<br>{{IPA|/\u0103j/}} {{angbr|ay}}\n| {{IPA|/\u0254j/}} {{angbr|oi}}\n|}\n\n{{Harvcoltxt|Thompson|1965}} says that in Hanoi, words spelled with ''\u01b0u'' and ''\u01b0\u01a1u'' are pronounced {{IPA|/iw, i\u0259w/}}, respectively, whereas other dialects in the Tonkin delta pronounce them as {{IPA|/\u0268w/}} and {{IPA|/\u0268\u0259w/}}. This observation is also made by {{Harvcoltxt|Ph\u1ea1m|2008}} and {{Harvcoltxt|Kirby|2011}}.\n\n==Final stops==\nWhen stops {{IPA|/p, t, k/}} occur at the end of words, they have [[no audible release]] ({{IPA|[p\u031a, t\u031a, k\u031a]}}):\n\n:{| cellpadding=\"5\" style=\"line-height: 1.0em;\"\n| ''\u0111\u00e1p''\n| 'to reply'\n| {{IPA|/\u0257ap/}}\n| \u2192\n| {{IPA|[\u0257ap\u031a]}}\n|-\n| ''m\u00e1t''\n| 'cool'\n| {{IPA|/mat/}}\n| \u2192\n| {{IPA|[mat\u031a]}}\n|-\n| ''kh\u00e1c''\n| 'different'\n| {{IPA|/xak/}}\n| \u2192\n| {{IPA|[xak\u031a]}}\n|}\n\nWhen the velar consonants {{IPA|/k, \u014b/}} are after {{IPA|/u, o, \u0254/}}, they are articulated with a simultaneous bilabial closure {{IPA|[k\u0361p\u031a, \u014b\u0361m]}} (i.e. [[doubly articulated]]) or are strongly [[labialization|labialized]] {{IPA|[k\u031a\u02b7, \u014b\u02b7]}}.\n\n:{| cellpadding=\"5\" style=\"line-height: 1.0em;\"\n| ''\u0111\u1ee5c''\n| 'muddy'\n| {{IPA|/\u0257uk/}}\n| \u2192\n| {{IPA|[\u0257uk\u0361p\u031a]}}, {{IPA|[\u0257uk\u031a\u02b7]}}\n|-\n| ''\u0111\u1ed9c''\n| 'poison'\n| {{IPA|/\u0257ok/}}\n| \u2192\n| {{IPA|[\u0257\u0259\u0306wk\u0361p\u031a]}}, {{IPA|[\u0257\u0259\u0306wk\u031a\u02b7]}}\n|-\n| ''\u0111\u1ecdc''\n| 'to read'\n| {{IPA|/\u0257\u0254k/}}\n| \u2192\n| {{IPA|[\u0257\u0103wk\u0361p\u031a]}}, {{IPA|[\u0257\u0103wk\u031a\u02b7]}}\n|-\n| ''ung''\n| 'cancer'\n| {{IPA|/u\u014b/}}\n| \u2192\n| {{IPA|[u\u014b\u0361m]}}, {{IPA|[u\u014b\u02b7]}}\n|-\n| ''\u00f4ng''\n| 'man'\n| {{IPA|/o\u014b/}}\n| \u2192\n| {{IPA|[\u0259\u0306w\u014b\u0361m]}}, {{IPA|[\u0259\u0306w\u014b\u02b7]}}\n|-\n| ''ong''\n| 'bee'\n| {{IPA|/\u0254\u014b/}}\n| \u2192\n| {{IPA|[\u0103w\u014b\u0361m]}}, {{IPA|[\u0103w\u014b\u02b7]}}\n|}\n\n===Hanoi finals===\n====Analysis of final ''ch'', ''nh''====\n\nThe pronunciation of syllable-final ''ch'' and ''nh'' in Hanoi Vietnamese has had different analyses. One analysis, that of {{Harvcoltxt|Thompson|1965}} has them as being phonemes {{IPA|/c, \u0272/}}, where {{IPA|/c/}} contrasts with both syllable-final ''t'' {{IPA|/t/}} and ''c'' {{IPA|/k/}} and {{IPA|/\u0272/}} contrasts with syllable-final ''n'' {{IPA|/n/}} and ''ng'' {{IPA|/\u014b/}}. Final {{IPA|/c, \u0272/}} is, then, identified with syllable-initial {{IPA|/c, \u0272/}}.\n\nAnother analysis has final {{angbr|ch}} and {{angbr|nh}} as representing predictable [[allophonic]] variants of the velar phonemes {{IPA|/k/}} and {{IPA|/\u014b/}} that occur after upper front vowels {{IPA|/i/}} (orthographic {{angbr|i}}) and {{IPA|/e/}} (orthographic {{angbr|\u00ea}}). This analysis interprets orthographic \u27e8ach\u27e9 and \u27e8anh\u27e9 as an underlying {{IPA|/\u025b/}}, which becomes phonetically open and diphthongized: {{IPA|/\u025bk/}} \u2192 {{IPA|[\u0103jk\u031f\u031a]}}, {{IPA|/\u025b\u014b/}} \u2192 {{IPA|[\u0103j\u014b\u031f]}}.<ref>Although there are some words where orthographic {{angbr|c}} and {{angbr|ng}} occur after {{IPA|/\u025b/}}, these words are few and are mostly loanwords or [[onomatopoeia]]</ref> This diphthongization also affects \u27e8\u00each\u27e9 and \u27e8\u00eanh\u27e9: {{IPA|/ek/}} \u2192 {{IPA|[\u0259\u0306jk\u031f\u031a]}}, {{IPA|/e\u014b/}} \u2192 {{IPA|[\u0259\u0306j\u014b\u031f]}}.\n\nArguments for the second analysis include the limited distribution of final {{IPA|[c]}} and {{IPA|[\u0272]}}, the gap in the distribution of {{IPA|[k]}} and {{IPA|[\u014b]}} which do not occur after {{IPA|[i]}} and {{IPA|[e]}}, the pronunciation of \u27e8ach\u27e9 and \u27e8anh\u27e9 as {{IPA|[\u025bc]}} and {{IPA|[\u025b\u0272]}} in certain conservative central dialects,<ref name=\"rhyme\"/> and the patterning of {{IPA|[k]}}~{{IPA|[c]}} and {{IPA|[\u014b]}}~{{IPA|[\u0272]}} in certain reduplicated words. Additionally, final {{IPA|[c]}} is not articulated as far forward as the initial {{IPA|[c]}}: {{IPA|[c]}} and {{IPA|[\u0272]}} are pre-velar {{IPA|[k\u031f, \u014b\u031f]}} with no alveolar contact.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Kirby|2011|p=383}}</ref>\n\nThe first analysis closely follows the surface pronunciation of a slightly different Hanoi dialect than the second. In this dialect, the {{IPA|/a/}} in {{IPA|/ac/}} and {{IPA|/a\u0272/}} is not diphthongized but is actually articulated more forward, approaching a front vowel {{IPA|[\u00e6]}}. This results in a three-way contrast between the rimes ''\u0103n'' {{IPA|[\u00e6\u0308n]}} vs. ''anh'' {{IPA|[\u00e6\u0308\u0272]}} vs. ''\u0103ng'' {{IPA|[\u00e6\u0308\u014b]}}. For this reason, a separate phonemic {{IPA|/\u0272/}} is posited.\n\n====Table of Hanoi finals====\nThe following [[syllable rime|rime]]s ending with [[velar consonant]]s have been [[diphthong]]ized in the Hanoi dialect:<ref name=\"rhyme\">{{Harvcoltxt|Ph\u1ea1m|2006}}</ref>\n\n:{| cellpadding=\"5\" style=\"line-height: 1.0em;\"\n| ''ong'', ''oc''\n| {{IPA|/\u0254\u014b/}}, {{IPA|/\u0254k/}}\n| \u2192\n| {{IPA|[\u0103w\u014b\u0361m]}}, {{IPA|[\u0103wk\u0361p\u031a]}}\n|-\n| ''\u00f4ng'', ''\u00f4c''\n| {{IPA|/o\u014b/}}, {{IPA|/ok/}}\n| \u2192\n| {{IPA|[\u0259\u0306w\u014b\u0361m]}}, {{IPA|[\u0259\u0306wk\u0361p\u031a]}}\n|-\n| ''anh'', ''ach''\n| {{IPA|/\u025b\u014b/}}, {{IPA|/\u025bk/}}\n| \u2192\n| {{IPA|[\u0103j\u014b\u031f]}}, {{IPA|[\u0103jk\u031f\u031a]}}\n|-\n| ''\u00eanh'', ''\u00each''\n| {{IPA|/e\u014b/}}, {{IPA|/ek/}}\n| \u2192\n| {{IPA|[\u0259\u0306j\u014b\u031f]}}, {{IPA|[\u0259\u0306jk\u031f\u031a]}}\n|}\n\nWith the above phonemic analyses, the following is a table of rimes ending in {{IPA|/n, t, \u014b, k/}} in the Hanoi dialect:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!\n! {{IPA|/\u0103/}}\n! {{IPA|/a/}}\n! {{IPA|/\u025b/}}\n! {{IPA|/\u0254/}}\n! {{IPA|/\u0259\u0306/}}\n! {{IPA|/\u0259/}}\n! {{IPA|/e/}}\n! {{IPA|/o/}}\n! {{IPA|/i/}}\n! {{IPA|/\u0268/}}\n! {{IPA|/u/}}\n! {{IPA|/i\u0259\u032f/}}\n! {{IPA|/\u0268\u0259\u032f/}}\n! {{IPA|/u\u0259\u032f/}}\n|-\n! {{IPA|/n/}}\n| ''\u0103n''\n| ''an''\n| ''en''\n| ''on''\n| ''\u00e2n''\n| ''\u01a1n''\n| ''\u00ean''\n| ''\u00f4n''\n| ''in''\n| ''\u01b0n''\n| ''un''\n| ''i\u00ean''\n| ''\u01b0\u01a1n''\n| ''u\u00f4n''\n|-\n! {{IPA|/t/}}\n| ''\u0103t''\n| ''at''\n| ''et''\n| ''ot''\n| ''\u00e2t''\n| ''\u01a1t''\n| ''\u00eat''\n| ''\u00f4t''\n| ''it''\n| ''\u01b0t''\n| ''ut''\n| ''i\u00eat''\n| ''\u01b0\u01a1t''\n| ''u\u00f4t''\n|-\n! {{IPA|/\u014b/}}\n| ''\u0103ng''\n| ''ang''\n| ''anh''\n| ''ong''\n| ''\u00e2ng''\n| \u2013\n| ''\u00eanh''\n| ''\u00f4ng''\n| ''inh''\n| ''\u01b0ng''\n| ''ung''\n| ''i\u00eang''\n| ''\u01b0\u01a1ng''\n| ''u\u00f4ng''\n|-\n! {{IPA|/k/}}\n| ''\u0103c''\n| ''ac''\n| ''ach''\n| ''oc''\n| ''\u00e2c''\n| \u2013\n| ''\u00each''\n| ''\u00f4c''\n| ''ich''\n| ''\u01b0c''\n| ''uc''\n| ''i\u00eac''\n| ''\u01b0\u01a1c''\n| ''u\u00f4c''\n|}\n\n===Saigon finals===\n====Merger of finals====\nWhile the variety of Vietnamese spoken in Hanoi has preserved finals faithfully from Middle Vietnamese, the variety spoken in Saigon has drastically changed its finals. Rimes ending in {{IPA|/k, \u014b/}} and {{IPA|/t, n/}} were merged except after {{IPA|/\u025b, \u0254/}}; in these rimes, {{IPA|/k, \u014b/}} is the underlying phoneme while {{IPA|[k\u0361p, \u014b\u0361m]}} occurs after rounded vowels {{IPA|/u, o/}} and {{IPA|[t, n]}} occurs after front vowels {{IPA|/i, e/}}.<ref name=\"rhyme\"/> Subsequently, vowels in labial-velar rimes became diphthongized while vowels in alveolar rimes became centralized<ref>{{citation | author=Ph\u1ea1m, Andrea H\u00f2a | year=2013 | title=Synchronic evidence for historical hypothesis \u2013 Vietnamese palatals | journal=Linguistic Association of Canada and the United States Forum |volume=39 |url= https://www.researchgate.net/publication/278035542}}</ref>in a similar fashion to the Hanoi dialect.\n\n====Table of Saigon finals====\nThe following [[syllable rime|rime]]s have been [[diphthong]]ized or [[relative_articulation#Centralized_vowels|centralized]] in the Saigon dialect:<ref name=\"rhyme\"/>\n:{| cellpadding=\"5\" style=\"line-height: 1.0em;\"\n| ''ong'', ''oc''\n| {{IPA|/\u0254\u014b\u0361m/}}, {{IPA|/\u0254k\u0361p/}}\n| \u2192\n| {{IPA|[\u0103w\u014b\u0361m]}}, {{IPA|[\u0103wk\u0361p\u031a]}}\n|-\n| ''\u00f4ng'', ''\u00f4c''\n| {{IPA|/o\u014b\u0361m/}}, {{IPA|/ok\u0361p/}}\n| \u2192\n| {{IPA|[\u0259\u0306w\u014b\u0361m]}}, {{IPA|[\u0259\u0306wk\u0361p\u031a]}}\n|-\n| ''anh'', ''ach''\n| {{IPA|/\u025bn/}}, {{IPA|/\u025bt/}}\n| \u2192\n| {{IPA|[\u0103n]}}, {{IPA|[\u0103t\u031a]}}\n|-\n| ''\u00ean'', ''\u00eat''\n| {{IPA|/en/}}, {{IPA|/et/}}\n| \u2192\n| {{IPA|[\u0259\u0306n]}}, {{IPA|[\u0259\u0306t\u031a]}}\n|-\n| ''in'', ''it''\n| {{IPA|/in/}}, {{IPA|/it/}}\n| \u2192\n| {{IPA|[\u0268n]}}, {{IPA|[\u0268t\u031a]}}\n|}\n\nWith the above phonemic analyses, the following is a table of rimes ending in {{IPA|/n, t, \u014b, k, \u014b\u0361m, k\u0361p/}} in the Saigon dialect:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!\n! {{IPA|/\u0103/}}\n! {{IPA|/a/}}\n! {{IPA|/\u025b/}}\n! {{IPA|/\u0254/}}\n! {{IPA|/\u0259\u0306/}}\n! {{IPA|/\u0259/}}\n! {{IPA|/e/}}\n! {{IPA|/o/}}\n! {{IPA|/i/}}\n! {{IPA|/\u0268/}}\n! {{IPA|/u/}}\n! {{IPA|/i\u0259\u032f/}}\n! {{IPA|/\u0268\u0259\u032f/}}\n! {{IPA|/u\u0259\u032f/}}\n|-\n! {{IPA|/n/}}\n|\n|\n| \u2013<br/>'''''anh'''''\n|\n|\n|\n| ''\u00ean''<br/>'''''\u00eanh'''''\n|\n| ''in''<br/>'''''inh'''''\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! {{IPA|/t/}}\n|\n|\n| \u2013<br/>'''''ach'''''\n|\n|\n|\n| ''\u00eat''<br/>'''''\u00each'''''\n|\n| ''it''<br/>'''''ich'''''\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! {{IPA|/\u014b/}}\n| '''''\u0103n'''''<br/>''\u0103ng''\n| '''''an'''''<br/>''ang''\n| '''''en'''''<br/>\u2013\n| '''''on'''''<br/>\u2013\n| '''''\u00e2n'''''<br/>''\u00e2ng''\n| '''''\u01a1n'''''<br/>\u2013\n|\n|\n|\n| '''''\u01b0n'''''<br/>''\u01b0ng''\n|\n| '''''i\u00ean'''''<br/>''i\u00eang''\n| '''''\u01b0\u01a1n'''''<br/>''\u01b0\u01a1ng''\n| '''''u\u00f4n'''''<br/>''u\u00f4ng''\n|-\n! {{IPA|/k/}}\n| '''''\u0103t'''''<br/>''\u0103c''\n| '''''at'''''<br/>''ac''\n| '''''et'''''<br/>\u2013\n| '''''ot'''''<br/>\u2013\n| '''''\u00e2t'''''<br/>''\u00e2c''\n| '''''\u01a1t'''''<br/>\u2013\n|\n|\n|\n| '''''\u01b0t'''''<br/>''\u01b0c''\n|\n| '''''i\u00eat'''''<br/>''i\u00eac''\n| '''''\u01b0\u01a1t'''''<br/>''\u01b0\u01a1c''\n| '''''u\u00f4t'''''<br/>''u\u00f4c''\n|-\n! {{IPA|/\u014b\u0361m/}}\n|\n|\n|\n| \u2013<br/>''ong''\n|\n|\n|\n| '''''\u00f4n'''''<br/>''\u00f4ng''\n|\n|\n| '''''un'''''<br/>''ung''\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! {{IPA|/k\u0361p/}}\n|\n|\n|\n| \u2013<br/>''oc''\n|\n|\n|\n| '''''\u00f4t'''''<br/>''\u00f4c''\n|\n|\n| '''''ut'''''<br/>''uc''\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! colspan=\"15\"|Combinations that have changed their pronunciation due to merger are bolded.\n|}\n\n==Tone==\nVietnamese vowels are all pronounced with an inherent [[Tone (linguistics)|tone]]. Tones differ in\n\n* pitch\n* length\n* contour melody\n* intensity\n* [[phonation]] (with or without accompanying constricted vocal cords)\n\nUnlike many Native American, African, and Chinese languages, Vietnamese tones do not rely solely on [[pitch contour]]. Vietnamese often uses instead a [[register complex]] (which is a combination of phonation type, pitch, length, vowel quality, etc.). So perhaps a better description would be that Vietnamese is a register language and not a \"pure\" tonal language.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Ph\u1ea1m|2003|p=93}}</ref>\n\nIn Vietnamese orthography, tone is indicated by diacritics written above or below the vowel.\n\n===Six-tone analysis===\n\nThere is much variation among speakers concerning how tone is realized phonetically. There are differences between varieties of Vietnamese spoken in the major geographic areas (northern, central, southern) and smaller differences within the major areas (e.g. Hanoi vs. other northern varieties). In addition, there seems to be variation among individuals. More research is needed to determine the remaining details of tone realization and the variation among speakers.\n\n====Northern varieties====\n\nThe six tones in the Hanoi and other northern varieties are:\n\n:{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n! [[Tone name]]\n! Tone ID\n! Description\n! Chao Tone Contour\n! Diacritic\n! Example\n|-\n| ''ngang'' \"level\"\n| A1\n| mid level\n| {{IPA|\u02e7}} (33)\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | (no mark)\n| ''ba'' ('three')\n|-\n| ''huy\u1ec1n'' \"deep\"\n| A2\n| low falling (breathy)\n| {{IPA|\u02e8\u02e9}} (21) or (31)\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''`'''\n| ''b\u00e0'' ('lady')\n|-\n| ''s\u1eafc'' \"sharp\"\n| B1\n| mid rising, tense\n| {{IPA|\u02e7\u02e5}} (35)\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''\u00b4'''\n| ''b\u00e1'' ('governor')\n|-\n| ''n\u1eb7ng'' \"heavy\"\n| B2\n| mid falling, glottalized, short\n| {{IPA|\u02e7\u02c0\u02e8\u0294}} (3\u02c02\u0294)<small> or </small>{{IPA|\u02e7\u02c0\u02e9\u0294}} (3\u02c01\u0294)\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''&nbsp;\u0323'''\n| ''b\u1ea1'' ('at random')\n|-\n| ''h\u1ecfi'' \"asking\"\n| C1\n| mid falling(-rising), harsh\n| {{IPA|\u02e7\u02e9\u02e7}} (313) or (323) or (31)\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''&nbsp;\u0309'''\n| ''b\u1ea3'' ('poison')\n|-\n| ''ng\u00e3'' \"tumbling\"\n| C2\n| mid rising, glottalized\n| {{IPA|\u02e7\u02c0\u02e5}} (3\u02c05) or (4\u02c05)\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''\u02dc'''\n| ''b\u00e3'' ('residue')\n|}\n\n[[File:VietnameseToneNorthern.png|thumb|upright=1.93|Northern Vietnamese (non-Hanoi) tones as uttered by a male speaker in isolation. From {{Harvcoltxt|Nguy\u1ec5n|Edmondson|1998}}]]\n[[File:VietnameseToneHanoi.png|thumb|upright=1.93|Hanoi tones as uttered by a female speaker in isolation. From {{Harvcoltxt|Nguy\u1ec5n|Edmondson|1998}}]]\n[[File:VietnameseToneHanoi2.png|thumb|upright=1.93|Hanoi tones as uttered by a different female speaker in isolation. From {{Harvcoltxt|Nguy\u1ec5n|Edmondson|1998}}]]\n\n'''Ngang tone:'''\n\n*The ''ngang'' tone is level at around the mid level (33) and is produced with [[modal voice]] [[phonation]] (i.e. with \"normal\" phonation). Alexandre de Rhodes (1651) describes this as \"level\"; {{Harvcoltxt|Nguy\u1ec5n|1997}} describes it as \"high (or mid) level\".\n\n'''Huy\u1ec1n tone:'''\n\n*The ''huy\u1ec1n'' tone starts low-mid and falls (21). Some Hanoi speakers start at a somewhat higher point (31). It is sometimes accompanied by [[breathy voice]] (or lax) phonation in some speakers, but this is lacking in other speakers: ''b\u00e0'' = {{IPA|[\u0253a\u02e8\u02e9]}}.<ref>For example, {{Harvcoltxt|Nguy\u1ec5n|Edmondson|1998}} show a male speaker from [[Nam \u0110\u1ecbnh Province|Nam \u0110\u1ecbnh]] with [[lax voice]] and a female speaker from Hanoi with breathy voice for the ''huy\u1ec1n'' tone while another male speaker from Hanoi has modal voice for the ''huy\u1ec1n''.</ref> Alexandre de Rhodes (1651) describes this as \"grave-lowering\"; {{Harvcoltxt|Nguy\u1ec5n|1997}} describes it as \"low falling\".\n\n'''H\u1ecfi tone:'''\n\n* The ''h\u1ecfi'' tone starts a mid level and falls. It starts with modal voice phonation, which moves increasingly toward [[tense voice]] with accompanying [[harsh voice]] (although the harsh voice seems to vary according to speaker). In Hanoi, the tone is mid falling (31). In other northern speakers, the tone is mid falling and then rises back to the mid level (313 or 323). This characteristic gives this tone its traditional description as \"dipping\". However, the falling-rising contour is most obvious in citation forms or when syllable-final; in other positions and when in fast speech, the rising contour is negligible. The ''h\u1ecfi'' also is relatively short compared with the other tones, but not as short as the ''n\u1eb7ng'' tone. Alexandre de Rhodes (1651) describes this as \"smooth-rising\"; {{Harvcoltxt|Nguy\u1ec5n|1997}} describes it as \"dipping-rising\".\n\n'''Ng\u00e3 tone:'''\n\n* The ''ng\u00e3'' tone is mid rising (35). Many speakers begin the vowel with modal voice, followed by strong [[creaky voice]] starting toward the middle of the vowel, which is then lessening as the end of the syllable is approached. Some speakers with more dramatic glottalization have a [[glottal stop]] closure in the middle of the vowel (i.e. as {{IPA|[V\u0294V]}}). In Hanoi Vietnamese, the tone starts at a higher pitch (45) than other northern speakers. Alexandre de Rhodes (1651) describes this as \"chesty-raised\"; {{Harvcoltxt|Nguy\u1ec5n|1997}} describes it as \"creaking-rising\".\n\n'''S\u1eafc tone:'''\n\n*The ''s\u1eafc'' tone starts as mid and then rises (35) in much the same way as the ''ng\u00e3'' tone. It is accompanied by [[tense voice]] phonation throughout the duration of the vowel. In some Hanoi speakers, the ''ng\u00e3'' tone is noticeably higher than the ''s\u1eafc'' tone, for example: ''s\u1eafc'' = {{IPA|\u02e7\u02e6}} (34); ''ng\u00e3'' = {{IPA|\u02e6\u02c0\u02e5}} (45). Alexandre de Rhodes (1651) describes this as \"acute-angry\"; {{Harvcoltxt|Nguy\u1ec5n|1997}} describes it as \"high (or mid) rising\".\n\n'''N\u1eb7ng tone:'''\n\n* The ''n\u1eb7ng'' tone starts mid or low-mid and rapidly falls in pitch (32 or 21). It starts with tense voice that becomes increasingly tense until the vowel ends in a glottal stop closure. This tone is noticeably shorter than the other tones. Alexandre de Rhodes (1651) describes this as \"chesty-heavy\"; {{Harvcoltxt|Nguy\u1ec5n|1997}} describes it as \"constricted\".\n\n====Southern varieties====\n{{Expand section|date=January 2011}}\nThe Southern variety is similar through all tones except for the ''n\u1eb7ng'' and ''ng\u00e3''/''h\u1ecfi'' tones.\nThe ''n\u1eb7ng'' tone are pronounced as low rising tone (12) [\u02e9\u02e8] in fast speech or low falling-rising tone (212) [\u02e8\u02e9\u02e8] in more careful utternce. \nThe ''ng\u00e3'' and ''h\u1ecfi'' tone are merged into a mid falling-rising (214) [\u02e8\u02e9\u02e6] which is somewhat similar ''h\u1ecfi'' tone of non-Hanoi Northern accent mentioned above.\n\n====North-central and Central varieties====\n\n{{Expand section|date=May 2008}}\n\nNorth-central and Central Vietnamese varieties are fairly similar with respect to tone although within the North-central dialect region there is considerable internal variation.\n\nIt is sometimes said (by people from other provinces) that people from [[Ngh\u1ec7 An]] pronounce every tone as a n\u1eb7ng tone.\n\n===Eight-tone analysis===\n\nAn older analysis assumes eight tones rather than six.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Ph\u1ea1m|2003|p=45}}</ref>  This follows the lead of traditional Chinese phonology.  In [[Middle Chinese]], syllables ending in a vowel or nasal allowed for three tonal distinctions, but syllables ending with {{IPA|/p/}}, {{IPA|/t/}} or {{IPA|/k/}} had no tonal distinctions.  Rather, they were consistently pronounced with a short high tone, which was called the [[entering tone]] and considered a fourth tone. Similar considerations lead to the identification of two additional tones in Vietnamese for syllables ending in {{IPA|/p/}}, {{IPA|/t/}}, {{IPA|/c/}} and {{IPA|/k/}}.  These are not [[phoneme|phonemically]] distinct from the ''s\u1eafc'' and ''n\u1eb7ng'' tones, however, and hence not considered as separate tones by modern linguists and are not distinguished in the orthography.\n\n==Syllables and phonotactics==\nAccording to {{Harvcoltxt|Hannas|1997}}, there are 4,500 to 4,800 possible spoken syllables (depending on dialect), and the standard national orthography (''[[Qu\u1ed1c Ng\u1eef]]'') can represent 6,200 syllables (''Qu\u1ed1c Ng\u1eef'' orthography represents more phonemic distinctions than are made by any one dialect).<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Hannas|1997|p=88}}</ref> A description of syllable structure and exploration of its patterning according to the Prosodic Analysis approach of J.R. Firth is given in Henderson (1966).<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Henderson|1966}}</ref>\n\nThe Vietnamese [[syllable|syllable structure]] follows the scheme:\n\n:(C<sub>1</sub>)(w)V(G|C<sub>2</sub>)+T\n\nwhere\n:{| cellpadding=\"7\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"background: #f9f9f9;\"\n| style=\"vertical-align: top;\" |\n* C<sub>1</sub> = initial consonant onset\n* w = labiovelar on-glide {{IPA|/w/}}\n* V = vowel nucleus\n| style=\"vertical-align: top;\" |\n* G = off-glide coda ({{IPA|/j/}} or {{IPA|/w/}})\n* C<sub>2</sub> = final consonant coda\n* T = tone.\n|}\n\nIn other words, a syllable has an obligatory nucleus and tone, and can have an optional consonant [[syllable onset|onset]], an optional on-glide {{IPA|/w/}}, and an optional [[syllable coda|coda]] or off-glide.\n\nMore explicitly, the syllable types are as follows:\n\n:{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"font-size: 85%; background: #f2f2f2;\"\n! Syllable\n! Example\n! Syllable\n! Example\n|-\n| V\n| \u00ea \"eh\"\n| wV\n| u\u1ec3 \"sluggish\"\n|-\n| VC\n| \u00e1m \"possess (by ghosts,.etc)\"\n| wVC\n| o\u00e1n \"bear a grudge\"\n|-\n| VC\n| \u1edbt \"capsicum\"\n| wVC\n| o\u1eaft \"little imp\"\n|-\n| CV\n| n\u1eef \"female\"\n| CwV\n| hu\u1ef7 \"cancel\"\n|-\n| CVC\n| c\u01a1m \"rice\"\n| CwVC\n| to\u00e1n \"math\"\n|-\n| CVC\n| t\u1ee9c \"angry\"\n| CwVC\n| ho\u1eb7c \"or\"\n|}\n\n'''C<sub>1</sub>:''' Any consonant may occur in as an onset with the following exceptions:\n* {{IPA|/p/}} does not occur in native Vietnamese words\n\n'''w:''' the onglide {{IPA|/w/}} (sometimes transcribed instead as [[labialization]] {{IPA|[\u02b7]}} on a preceding consonant):\n\n* does not occur after labial consonants {{IPA|/\u0253, f, v, m/}}\n* does not occur after {{IPA|/n/}} in native Vietnamese words (it occurs in uncommon [[Sino-Vietnamese vocabulary|Sino-Vietnamese]] borrowings)\n\n'''V:''' The vowel nucleus V may be any of the following 14 monophthongs or diphthongs: {{IPA|/i, \u0268, u, e, \u0259, o, \u025b, \u0259\u0306, \u0254, \u0103, a, i\u0259\u032f, \u0268\u0259\u032f, u\u0259\u032f/}}.\n\n'''G:''' The offglide may be {{IPA|/j/}} or {{IPA|/w/}}. Together, V and G must form one of the diphthongs or triphthongs listed in the section on Vowels.\n* offglide {{IPA|/j/}} does not follow the front vowels {{IPA|/i, e, \u025b, i\u0259\u032f/}}\n* offglide {{IPA|/w/}} does not follow the rounded vowels {{IPA|/u, o, \u0254, u\u0259\u032f/}}\n* with some exceptions (such as ''[[wikt:khu\u1ef7u tay#Vietnamese|khu\u1ef7u tay]]'' \"elbow\"), the offglide {{IPA|/w/}} cannot occur if the syllable contains a {{IPA|/w/}} onglide\n\n'''C<sub>2</sub>:''' The optional coda C<sub>2</sub> is restricted to labial, coronal, and velar stops and nasals {{IPA|/p, t, k, m, n, \u014b/}}, which cannot cooccur with the offglides {{IPA|/j, w/}}.\n\n'''T:''' Syllables are spoken with an inherent [[tone (linguistics)|tone contour]]:\n* Six tone contours are possible for syllables with offglides {{IPA|/j, w/}}, closed syllables with nasal codas {{IPA|/m, n, \u014b/}}, and [[open syllable]]s\u2014i.e., those without consonant codas {{IPA|/p, t, k/}}.\n* If the syllable is closed with one of the oral stops {{IPA|/p, t, k/}}, only two contours are possible: the ''s\u1eafc'' and the ''n\u1eb7ng'' tones.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size: 90%\"\n|+ Common Vietnamese rimes {{ref|Notes|[Notes]}}\n! rowspan=\"2\" colspan=\"2\" |\n! Zero coda\n! colspan=\"2\" | Off-glide coda\n! colspan=\"3\" | Nasal consonant coda\n! colspan=\"3\" | Stop consonant coda\n|-\n! {{IPA|\u2205}} || {{IPA|/j/}} || {{IPA|/w/}} || {{IPA|/m/}} || {{IPA|/n/}} || {{IPA|/\u014b/}} || {{IPA|/p/}} || {{IPA|/t/}} || {{IPA|/k/}}\n|-\n! rowspan=\"14\" style=\"width: 5px;\" | Vowel nucleus\n! {{IPA|/\u0103/}}\n| || ''\u1ea1y''<br>{{IPA|[\u0103j]}} || ''\u1ea1u''<br>{{IPA|[\u0103w]}} || ''\u1eb7m''<br>{{IPA|[\u0103m]}} || ''\u1eb7n''<br>{{IPA|[\u0103n]}} || ''\u1eb7ng''<br>{{IPA|[\u0103\u014b]}} || ''\u1eb7p''<br>{{IPA|[\u0103p]}} || ''\u1eb7t''<br>{{IPA|[\u0103t]}} || ''\u1eb7c''<br>{{IPA|[\u0103k]}}\n|-\n! {{IPA|/a/}}\n| ''\u1ea1'', ''(gi)\u00e0'', ''(gi)\u1ea3'', ''(gi)\u00e3'', ''(gi)\u00e1''<br>{{IPA|[a]}} || ''\u1ea1i''<br>{{IPA|[aj]}} || ''\u1ea1o''<br>{{IPA|[aw]}} || ''\u1ea1m''<br>{{IPA|[am]}} || ''\u1ea1n''<br>{{IPA|[an]}} || ''\u1ea1ng''<br>{{IPA|[a\u014b]}} || ''\u1ea1p''<br>{{IPA|[ap]}} || ''\u1ea1t''<br>{{IPA|[at]}} || ''\u1ea1c''<br>{{IPA|[ak]}}\n|-\n! {{IPA|/\u025b/}}\n| ''\u1eb9''<br>{{IPA|[\u025b]}} || || ''\u1eb9o''<br>{{IPA|[\u025bw]}} || ''\u1eb9m''<br>{{IPA|[\u025bm]}} || ''\u1eb9n''<br>{{IPA|[\u025bn]}} || ''\u1ea1nh''<br>{{IPA|[\u0103j\u014b]}} || ''\u1eb9p''<br>{{IPA|[\u025bp]}} || ''\u1eb9t''<br>{{IPA|[\u025bt]}} || ''\u1ea1ch''<br>{{IPA|[\u0103jk]}}\n|-\n! {{IPA|/\u0254/}}\n| ''\u1ecd''<br>{{IPA|[\u0254]}} || ''\u1ecdi''<br>{{IPA|[\u0254j]}} || || ''\u1ecdm''<br>{{IPA|[\u0254m]}} || ''\u1ecdn''<br>{{IPA|[\u0254n]}} || ''\u1ecdng''<br>{{IPA|[\u0103w\u014b]}} || ''\u1ecdp''<br>{{IPA|[\u0254p]}} || ''\u1ecdt''<br>{{IPA|[\u0254t]}} || ''\u1ecdc''<br>{{IPA|[\u0103wk]}}\n|-\n! {{IPA|/\u0259\u0306/}}\n| || ''\u1eady''<br>{{IPA|[\u0259\u0306j]}} || ''\u1eadu''<br>{{IPA|[\u0259\u0306w]}} || ''\u1eadm''<br>{{IPA|[\u0259\u0306m]}} || ''\u1eadn''<br>{{IPA|[\u0259\u0306n]}} || ''\u1eadng''<br>{{IPA|[\u0259\u0306\u014b]}} || ''\u1eadp''<br>{{IPA|[\u0259\u0306p]}} || ''\u1eadt''<br>{{IPA|[\u0259\u0306t]}} || ''\u1eadc''<br>{{IPA|[\u0259\u0306k]}}\n|-\n! {{IPA|/\u0259/}}\n| ''\u1ee3''<br>{{IPA|[\u0259]}} || ''\u1ee3i''<br>{{IPA|[\u0259j]}} || || ''\u1ee3m''<br>{{IPA|[\u0259m]}} || ''\u1ee3n''<br>{{IPA|[\u0259n]}} || || ''\u1ee3p''<br>{{IPA|[\u0259p]}} || ''\u1ee3t''<br>{{IPA|[\u0259t]}} ||\n|-\n! {{IPA|/e/}}\n| ''\u1ec7''<br>{{IPA|[e]}} || || ''\u1ec7u''<br>{{IPA|[ew]}} || ''\u1ec7m''<br>{{IPA|[em]}} || ''\u1ec7n''<br>{{IPA|[en]}} || ''\u1ec7nh''<br>{{IPA|[\u0259\u0306j\u014b]}} || ''\u1ec7p''<br>{{IPA|[ep]}} || ''\u1ec7t''<br>{{IPA|[et]}} || ''\u1ec7ch''<br>{{IPA|[\u0259\u0306jk]}}\n|-\n! {{IPA|/o/}}\n| ''\u1ed9''<br>{{IPA|[o]}} || ''\u1ed9i''<br>{{IPA|[oj]}} || || ''\u1ed9m''<br>{{IPA|[om]}} || ''\u1ed